{"title_page": "Foundation for Defense of Democracies", "text_new": "{{infobox organization\n| name = Foundation for Defense of Democracies\n| image = Foundation for Defense of Democracies.svg\n| image_size = 250px\n| abbreviation = FDD\n| formation = {{start date and age|2001}}\n| type = [[501(c)(3) organization]]\n| tax_id = 13-4174402\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = [[Clifford May]]\n| leader_title2 = CEO\n| leader_name2  = [[Mark Dubowitz]]\n| website = {{url|www.FDD.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Foundation for Defense of Democracies''' ('''FDD''') is a policy institute (or [[think tank]]) based in [[Washington, D.C.]], focusing on national security and foreign policy. \n\nIts political leanings have been described variously as nonpartisan,<ref name=LATIMES>{{cite news|last=Richter|first=Paul|title=Chinese bank pulls out of Pakistan-Iran pipeline project|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/mar/14/world/la-fg-pakistan-china-pipeline-20120315|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=March 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301031248/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/mar/14/world/la-fg-pakistan-china-pipeline-20120315|archive-date=2013-03-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=NPR>{{cite news|last=NPR Staff|title=Better To Elect Islamists Than Have Dictators?|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/10/07/162457484/better-to-elect-islamists-than-have-dictators|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=NPR|date=October 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325232955/http://www.npr.org/2012/10/07/162457484/better-to-elect-islamists-than-have-dictators|archive-date=2013-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Forward>{{cite news|last=Guttman|first=Nathan|title=Laying Groundwork for Life After Syria's Assad|url=http://forward.com/articles/168511/laying-groundwork-for-life-after-syrias-assad/?p=all#ixzz2GnfpD7EB|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=Forward|date=January 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403174553/http://forward.com/articles/168511/laying-groundwork-for-life-after-syrias-assad/?p=all#ixzz2GnfpD7EB#ixzz2GnfpD7EB|archive-date=2013-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=C-SPAN>{{cite web|title=Foreign Policy Experts Examine Democracies in the Mideast|url=http://www.c-span.org/Events/Foreign-Policy-Experts-Examine-Democracies-in-the-Mideast/10737436364/|publisher=C-SPAN|accessdate=14 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609131835/http://www.c-span.org/Events/Foreign-Policy-Experts-Examine-Democracies-in-the-Mideast/10737436364/|archive-date=2013-06-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=AP>{{cite news|last=Flaccus|first=Gillian|title=2 of 4 terror suspects were new Islamic converts|url=http://www.nwherald.com/2012/11/22/2-of-4-terror-suspects-were-new-islamic-converts/awq89hd/|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=The Associated Press|date=November 22, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607222422/http://www.nwherald.com/2012/11/22/2-of-4-terror-suspects-were-new-islamic-converts/awq89hd/|archive-date=2013-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref> [[War hawk|hawkish]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/25/white-house-blindsided-by-iranian-foreign-minister-zarifs-g7-appearance.html |title=white house blindsided by iranian foreign minister zarif's appearance |last=Lee |first=Carol |publisher=cnbc.com |accessdate=2019-09-20 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920222612/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/25/white-house-blindsided-by-iranian-foreign-minister-zarifs-g7-appearance.html |archive-date=2019-09-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How Trump trips up his own Afghanistan peace efforts|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/16/trump-afghanistan-peace-1668390|last=Wilson|first=Mark|publisher=politico.com|accessdate=2019-09-20|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914100424/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/16/trump-afghanistan-peace-1668390|archive-date=2019-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/13/us/politics/mark-dubowitz-iran-deal.html|title=He Was a Tireless Critic of the Iran Deal. Now He Insists He Wanted to Save It.|date=2018-05-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514144653/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/13/us/politics/mark-dubowitz-iran-deal.html|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/08/mcmaster-white-house-danger-to-the-constitution-1418268|title=McMaster blasts former colleagues as 'danger to the Constitution'|last=Morgan|first=Wesley|date=May 9, 2019|website=Politico}}</ref> and [[neoconservative]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Peter|title=Obama's new head boy|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-politics/9891755/Obamas-new-head-boy.html|accessdate=12 March 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph (UK)|date=February 24, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228034030/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-politics/9891755/Obamas-new-head-boy.html|archive-date=2013-02-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"amconserv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/most-favored-democracy/|title=Most Favored Democracy|publisher=The American Conservative|accessdate=2013-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424215942/http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/most-favored-democracy/|archive-date=2013-04-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=csmonitor>{{cite news|last=Jonsson|first=Patrik|title=Shooting of two soldiers in Little Rock puts focus on 'lone wolf' Islamic extremists|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2009/0611/p02s01-usju.html|accessdate=13 March 2013|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=June 11, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130406031548/http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2009/0611/p02s01-usju.html|archive-date=2013-04-06|url-status=live}}</ref> FDD holds events throughout the year, including its annual Washington Forum, briefings on Capitol Hill, expert roundtables for public officials, diplomats, and military officers, book releases, and panel discussions and debates within the policy community. Clifford D. May is FDD\u2019s founder and president. Mark Dubowitz serves as FDD\u00b4s CEO.\n\nFDD has been identified as part of the [[Israel lobby in the United States]] by several scholarly sources.<ref>For example, see the following sources:\n*{{citation|first=Muhammad Idrees|last=Ahmad|title=Road to Iraq: The Making of a Neoconservative War|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780748693054|page=179|quote=The [Israel] lobby has insulated itself with a network of satellite institutions and alliances all invested in cultivating the view that Israeli and US interests are identical... It consists of... think thanks such as WINEP, JINSA, AEI, CSP, the Saban Center for Middle East Policy, FDD, and the defence/national security programmes of the Hudson Institute and the Heritage Foundation...}}\n*{{citation|first1=Ofira|last1=Seliktar|first2=Farhad|last2=Rezaei|title=Iran, Israel, and the United States: The Politics of Counter-Proliferation Intelligence|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2018|isbn=9781498569767|page=168|quote=The Israel lobby stalwarts\u2014the WINEP, the FDD, the Israel Project, the Jewish National Security Affairs (JINSA), CSP, and UANI, among others\u2014produced a considerable number of reports, policy papers, articles, and op-eds, and their reprasantatives regularly testified before Congress.}}\n*{{citation|last1=Mearsheimer|first1=John J.|last2=Stephen|first2=Walt|title=The Israel Lobby and U.S. Foreign Policy|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|location=New York|year=2007|pages=128\u2013130|isbn=978-0-374-17772-0|quote=The [Israel] lobby's drift to the right has been reinforced by the emergence of the neoconservatives... The think tanks and advocacy groups most closely associated with these neoconservatives are the American Enterprise Institute (AEI), the Center for Security Policy (CSP), the Hudson Institute, the Foundation for Defense of Democracies (FDD), the Jewish Institute for National Security Affairs (JINSA), the Middle East Forum (MEF), the Project for a New American Century (PNAC), and the Washington Institute for Near East Policy (WINEP). Virtually all neoconservatives are strongly committed to Israel, a point they emphasize openly and unapologetically.}}\n*{{citation|first=Sujata|last=Ashwarya|title=India-Iran Relations: Progress, Problems and Prospects|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=9781351987073|page=179|quote=In a 155-page report \u201cUS Non-proliferation Strategy for the Changing Middle East,\u201d co-authored by the head of a right-wing pro-Israel lobby group, the Foundation for Defence of Democracies (FDD), Mark Dubowitz, states that...}}</ref>\n== Funding ==\n=== 2001\u20132004 ===\nIn 2011, news website ''[[ThinkProgress]]'' published FDD's [[Form 990]] documents<ref>{{cite web|url=http://d35brb9zkkbdsd.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/FDDdonors.pdf|title=Form 990|publisher=ThinkProgress|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205160813/http://d35brb9zkkbdsd.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/FDDdonors.pdf|archive-date=2014-12-05|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> that revealed where FDD funding came from, from 2001 to 2004. Top donors included:\n*[[Roland Arnall]]: $1,802,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Edgar Bronfman, Sr.|Edgar M.]] and [[Charles Bronfman]]: $1,050,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Michael Steinhardt]]: $850,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n* Abramson Family Foundation (of [[Leonard Abramson]]): $822,523<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Bernard Marcus]]: $600,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Lewis Ranieri]]: $350,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\nOther notable donors who gave lesser money during the same period were:\n*[[Haim Saban]]<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Jennifer Laszlo Mizrahi]]<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Douglas J. Feith]]<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n\n=== 2008\u20132011 ===\nFDD's [[IRS tax forms#Schedules|Schedule A]] documents filed by the end of the 2011 tax year, indicates that the organization from 2008 to 2011 was funded more than $20,000,000,<ref name=\"Salon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.salon.com/2013/08/05/home_depot_founder\u2019s_quiet_10_million_right_wing_investment/|title=Home Depot founder's quiet $10 million right-wing investment|author=Eli Clifton|date=2013-06-08|access-date=2019-02-07|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126101741/https://www.salon.com/2013/08/05/home_depot_founder%E2%80%99s_quiet_10_million_right_wing_investment/|archive-date=2019-01-26|work=Salon}}</ref> and the top three donors were:\n*[[Bernard Marcus]]: $10,745,000<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n*[[Paul Singer (businessman)|Paul Singer]]: $3,600,000<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n*[[Sheldon Adelson]]: $1,510,059<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n=== 2017 ===\nIn 2018, [[Associated Press|AP]] reported that the [[United Arab Emirates]] has wired $2,500,000 to the FDD through [[Elliott Broidy]] and [[George Nader (businessman)|George Nader]], to host a conference amidst [[Qatar diplomatic crisis]] about the country's role as a state-sponsor of terrorism.<ref name=\"AP2018\"/> FDD stated that it does not accept money from foreign governments, adding that \"[a]s is our funding policy, we asked if his funding was connected to any foreign governments or if he had business contracts in the Gulf. He assured us that he did not\".<ref name=\"AP2018\">{{citation|first1=Desmond|last1=Butler|first2=Tom|last2=LoBianco|first3=Bradley|last3=Klapper|first4=Chad|last4=Day|first5=Richard|last5=Lardner|url=https://apnews.com/2e2f7f54c93e4427ad40f3b6cb95d6b1|title=Witness in Mueller probe aided UAE agenda in Congress|work=The Associated Press|access-date=10 January 2020|date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Adam Hanieh]] states that the FDD high-profile conference of 23 May 2017 was in line with UAE's policy at the time, which officially alleged that Qatar finances Islamist groups, adding that emails leaked shortly after show that UAE's Ambassador [[Yousef Al Otaiba]] had a \"cosy relationship\" with the FDD, and had reviewed the remarks made by [[Robert Gates]] at the convention.<ref>{{citation|first=Adam|last=Hanieh|title=Money, Markets, and Monarchies: The Gulf Cooperation Council and the Political Economy of the Contemporary Middle East|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2018|isbn=9781108429146|page=247}}</ref>\n\n=== Others ===\nAdditionally, it is known that as of 2016, FDD has received donations from the following institutions:\n{{Col-begin}}{{Col-break}}\n* Abstraction Fund<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\">{{citation|first1=David|last1=Cronin|first2=Sarah|last2=Marusek|first3=David|last3=Miller|title=The Israel Lobby and the European Union|url=https://purehost.bath.ac.uk/ws/portalfiles/portal/167838098/PII_IsraelLobbyEUreport2016_Cronin_Marusek_Miller.pdf|year=2016|location=Glasgow|publisher=Public Interest Investigations|isbn=978-0-9570274-7-3|via=University of Bath}}</ref>{{rp|24}}\n* [[Roger Hertog#Philanthropy|Hertog Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|24}}\n* Jacobson Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* [[Seth Klarman#Philanthropy|Klarman Family Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* [[Koret Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* [[Milstein Family Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* Nathan Seter Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* Newton and Rochelle Becker Charitable Trust<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|31}}\n{{Col-break}}\n* [[Ed Snider#Nonprofit organizations|Snider Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|31}}\n* Hochberg Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|39}}\n* Marcus Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|39}}\n* Bodman Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|39}}\n* Emerson Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|41}}\n* Eris & Larry Field Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|41}}\n* Rita & Irwin Hochberg Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|42}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Activities==\n===The Iran Project===\nIran's government officially threatened FDD and its CEO Mark Dubowitz, enacting sanctions against the CEO, and implicitly threatening the think tank with force from the Iranian state's \"security apparatus,\" as implied in Tehran's own official announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.mehrnews.com/news/149247/Iran-sanctions-Washington-based-FDD-for-role-in-intensifying|title=Iran sanctions Washington-based FDD for role in intensifying 'US economic terrorism'|date=2019-08-24|website=Mehr News Agency|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://en.mfa.ir/portal/newsview/50334| title=Foreign Ministry Blacklists 'Foundation for Defence of Democracies'| date=August 24, 2019| publisher=Islamic Republic of Iran: Ministry of Foreign Affairs}}</ref>\n\nLed by CEO<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fdd.org/team/mark-dubowitz/|title=FDD {{!}} Mark Dubowitz|website=FDD|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130110307/https://www.fdd.org/team/mark-dubowitz/|archive-date=2019-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mark Dubowitz]], FDD's [[Iran]] Program<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fdd.org/projects/iran-program/|title=FDD {{!}} Iran Program|website=FDD|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130110532/https://www.fdd.org/projects/iran-program/|archive-date=2019-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref> seeks to \"address the threat posed by the Islamic Republic of Iran to America and its allies, FDD conducts detailed research, develops actionable and comprehensive policy options, and appears regularly in media.\" <ref name=\":0\" /> FDD says it does this through attacking Iran's \"most vulnerable points: its worldwide media operations, its standing in the United States and Europe, its finances, and its efforts to support terrorist activities abroad\".<ref name=Iran>{{cite web|title=Iran Research|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826113320/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran/|archive-date=2012-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref> Specifically, FDD concerns itself with Iran's nuclear ambitions through its Iran Energy Project<ref name=\"Iran Energy Project\">{{cite web|title=Iran Energy Project|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-energy-project/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316225301/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-energy-project/|archive-date=2013-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref> and Iran's [[Human rights in Iran|human rights abuses]] through its Iran Human Rights Project.<ref name=\"Human Rights Project\">{{cite web|title=Iran Human Rights Project|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-human-rights-project/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317061125/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-human-rights-project/|archive-date=17 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, FDD founded the Iran Energy Project which \"conducts extensive research on ways to deny the Iranian regime the profits of [[Energy in Iran|its energy sector]]\".<ref name=\"Iran Sanctions\">{{cite web|title=Iran - Energy|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran-sanctions/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121185544/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran-sanctions/|archive-date=2013-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' credited FDD with bringing \"the idea of gasoline sanctions to political attention.\"<ref name=\"WSJ Iran sanctions\">{{cite news|last=Editorial|title=Pain Iran Can Believe In|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793752240531921|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=2009-03-25|access-date=2017-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010125257/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793752240531921|archive-date=2017-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref> FDD's bi-partisan approach to advocating sanctions legislation has earned praise from Congressmen in both parties. Congressman [[Howard Berman]] (D-CA) thanked the organization saying \"FDD has been one the most committed and creative voices in Washington regarding the Iran nuclear issue and specifically [[Sanctions against Iran|Iran sanctions]]\".<ref name=Berman>{{cite web|title=Remarks by Rep. Howard Berman (D-CA)|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/remarks-by-rep-howard-berman-d-ca/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529173053/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/remarks-by-rep-howard-berman-d-ca/|archive-date=29 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> FDD's efforts to target the Iranian regime's finances has gone beyond energy sanctions. The organization pushed for sanctions against the [[Central Bank of the Islamic Republic of Iran]] and its use of [[Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication]] (SWIFT) to perform transactions. According to ''The Wall Street Journal'', FDD \"has done most of the spadework on the issue\".<ref name=\"WSJ Swift\">{{cite news|last=Editorial|title=Swift Sanctions on Iran|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203718504577178902535754464|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=February 1, 2012|access-date=2017-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010125327/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203718504577178902535754464|archive-date=2017-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===FDD's Long War Journal===\n[[FDD's Long War Journal]] is a FDD project dedicated to reporting the [[Global War on Terror]] launched by the United States and its allies following the attacks of September 11, 2001. Under the direction of FDD senior fellows [[Bill Roggio]] and Thomas Joscelyn, this website covers stories about countries such as [[Afghanistan]], [[Pakistan]], [[Somalia]], [[Syria]], and [[Iraq]] and follows the actions of [[al Qaeda]] and its affiliates.<ref name=\"LWJ about\">{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/about.php|publisher=The Long War Journal|accessdate=30 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201031735/http://www.longwarjournal.org/about.php|archive-date=2013-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'', \"Roggio's greatest service, then, may be the way he picks up where the mainstream press leaves off, giving readers a simultaneously more specific and holistic understanding of the battlefield\".<ref name=CJR>{{cite news|last=Mcleary|first=Paul|title=Blogging the long war: Bill Roggio wants to be your source for conflict coverage|url=http://www.cjr.org/profile/blogging_the_long_war_1.php|newspaper=Columbia Journalism Review|date=March\u2013April 2008}}</ref>\n\n===The Syria Project===\nFor years, [[Syria]] has been a focus of FDD's research because of its alignment with Iran and support for organizations such as [[Hezbollah]].<ref name=\"Syria NOW\">{{cite web|last=Badran|first=Tony|title=A Syria in minor key|url=https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/commentaryanalysis/a_syria_in_minor_key|publisher=NOW Lebanon|accessdate=31 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118200359/https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/commentaryanalysis/a_syria_in_minor_key|archive-date=2013-01-18|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, as the [[Arab Spring]] spread to Syria, FDD launched \"The Syria Project\" to support dissident efforts in removing the Assad regime.<ref name=\"Syria Project\">{{cite web|title=The Syria Project|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/the-syria-project/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=31 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141124172024/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/the-syria-project/|archive-date=2014-11-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In that effort, FDD facilitated a Skype call between dissidents and U.S. journalists in 2012<ref name=\"CNN Skype\">{{cite news|last=Zuka|first=Muhammad|title=A Syrian resistance leader's plea to the world|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/02/16/opinion/zuka-syria-resistance-leader/index.html|newspaper=CNN|date=February 12, 2012|access-date=2013-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827094442/http://www.cnn.com/2012/02/16/opinion/zuka-syria-resistance-leader/index.html|archive-date=2012-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref> and produced multiple studies and memos urging U.S. officials to act.<ref name=Milestones>{{cite web|title=Project Milestones|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/action-taken/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=31 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602090127/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/action-taken/|archive-date=2 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nThe [[International Relations Center]] features a report on the foundation on its \"Right Web\" website, a program of the [[Centre-left politics|left of center]]<ref>{{cite web|work=Transnational Institute|publisher=Transnational Institute|title=Left-wing thinkers|last=Blumenthal|first=Sidney|authorlink=Sidney Blumenthal|date=July 30, 1986|url=http://tni.org/archives/media_ips-wp1986|accessdate=2010-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607163250/http://www.tni.org//archives/media_ips-wp1986|archive-date=2011-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=CBC Radio Canada|title=Review: Discussion on The Current about minimum wages and executive compensation, January 29, 2007|date=June 14, 2007|url=http://www.cbc.ca/ombudsman/ombudsmanweb/41.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723003655/http://www.cbc.ca/ombudsman/ombudsmanweb/41.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 23, 2012|accessdate=2010-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Fairness & Accuracy in Reporting|publisher=FAIR|title=Heritage Clones in the Heartland|last=Soley|first=Lawrence|date=September\u2013October 1998|url=http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1430|accessdate=2010-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107203209/http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1430|archive-date=2010-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=FrontPageMagazine|publisher=FrontPageMagazine|title=The ABC's of Media Bias|last=Ponte|first=Lowell|date=October 14, 2004|url=http://97.74.65.51/readArticle.aspx?ARTID=10987|accessdate=2010-11-04}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> think tank [[Institute for Policy Studies]]<ref>{{cite web|title=About Right Web|url=http://rightweb.irc-online.org/about/|publisher=RightWeb|access-date=2013-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121194542/http://rightweb.irc-online.org/about/|archive-date=2013-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref> which, according to its mission statement, seeks to \"check the [[Militarism|militaristic]] drift of the country\". The report states that \"although the FDD is an ardent critic of terrorism, it has not criticized actions taken by Israel against Palestinians that arguably fall into this category\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rightweb.irc-online.org/profile/Foundation_for_Defense_of_Democracies |title=Foundation for Defense of Democracies - Profile - Right Web - Institute for Policy Studies |publisher=Rightweb.irc-online.org |accessdate=2011-08-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105015114/http://www.rightweb.irc-online.org/profile/Foundation_for_Defense_of_Democracies |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref>\n\nThe left-leaning political blog ''[[ThinkProgress]]'' has criticized FDD for \"alarmist rhetoric and fear mongering\",<ref name=thinkprogress>{{cite news|last1=Clifton|first1=Eli|title=EXCLUSIVE: Documents Shed Light On Those Underwriting The Foundation For Defense Of Democracies|url=http://thinkprogress.org/security/2011/07/19/271431/fdd-donors/|work=ThinkProgress|date=19 July 2011|access-date=2014-11-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106221421/http://thinkprogress.org/security/2011/07/19/271431/fdd-donors/|archive-date=2014-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=Your WP:Partisan source|date=August 2016}} for example in April 2002 when they aired a 30-second [[television ad]] campaign called \"Suicide Strategy\" that was described by critics as \"conflating\" Palestinian leader [[Yasser Arafat]] with the likes of [[Osama bin Laden]] and [[Saddam Hussein]]. As FDD explained it: \"a militant [[Islamic terrorism|Islamic terrorist]] who 'martyrs' himself by [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacking a plane]] and flying it into the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]]\"\u2014i.e., the [[September&nbsp;11 attacks]]\u2014\"is no different from a militant Islamic terrorist who 'martyrs' himself by [[Suicide attack|strapping explosives to his body and walking into a hotel]]\"\u2014i.e., [[List of Palestinian suicide attacks|Palestinian suicide attacks]].\n\n==Select publications ==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [http://www.defenddemocracy.org/content/uploads/documents/Small_arms_Report.pdf \"The Tactical and Strategic Use of Small Arms by Terrorists\"], Daveed Gartenstein-Ross and Daniel Trombly, October 2012.\n* \"Terror in the Peaceable Kingdom: Understanding and Addressing Violent Extremism in Canada\", Daveed Gartenstein-Ross and Senator [[Linda Frum]], July 2012.\n* \"Facebook Fatwa: Saudi Clerics, Wahhabi Islam and Social Media\", Jonathan Schanzer and Steven Miller, May 2012.\n* ''The Pasdaran: Inside Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps'', Emanuele Ottolenghi, 2011.\n* ''Palestinian Pulse: What Policymakers Can Learn From Palestinian Social Media'', Jonathan Schanzer and Mark Dubowitz, 2010.\n* ''The Afghanistan-Pakistan Theater: Militant Islam, Security & Stability'', Clifford D. May and Daveed Gartenstein-Ross, 2010.\n* ''From Energy Crisis to Energy Security'', Clifford D. May and Daveed Gartenstein-Ross, 2008.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.defenddemocracy.org/ Official website] \n{{Neoconservatism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foundation For Defense Of Democracies}}\n[[Category:Think tanks established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Foundations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Neoconservatism]]\n[[Category:Conservative organizations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox organization\n| name = Foundation for Defense of Democracies\n| image = Foundation for Defense of Democracies.svg\n| image_size = 250px\n| abbreviation = FDD\n| formation = {{start date and age|2001}}\n| type = [[501(c)(3) organization]]\n| tax_id = 13-4174402\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = [[Clifford May]]\n| leader_title2 = CEO\n| leader_name2  = [[Mark Dubowitz]]\n| website = {{url|www.FDD.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Foundation for Defense of Democracies''' ('''FDD''') is a policy institute (or [[think tank]]) based in [[Washington, D.C.]], focusing on national security and foreign policy. Its political leanings have been described variously as nonpartisan,<ref name=LATIMES>{{cite news|last=Richter|first=Paul|title=Chinese bank pulls out of Pakistan-Iran pipeline project|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/mar/14/world/la-fg-pakistan-china-pipeline-20120315|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=March 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301031248/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/mar/14/world/la-fg-pakistan-china-pipeline-20120315|archive-date=2013-03-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=NPR>{{cite news|last=NPR Staff|title=Better To Elect Islamists Than Have Dictators?|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/10/07/162457484/better-to-elect-islamists-than-have-dictators|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=NPR|date=October 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325232955/http://www.npr.org/2012/10/07/162457484/better-to-elect-islamists-than-have-dictators|archive-date=2013-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Forward>{{cite news|last=Guttman|first=Nathan|title=Laying Groundwork for Life After Syria's Assad|url=http://forward.com/articles/168511/laying-groundwork-for-life-after-syrias-assad/?p=all#ixzz2GnfpD7EB|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=Forward|date=January 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403174553/http://forward.com/articles/168511/laying-groundwork-for-life-after-syrias-assad/?p=all#ixzz2GnfpD7EB#ixzz2GnfpD7EB|archive-date=2013-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=C-SPAN>{{cite web|title=Foreign Policy Experts Examine Democracies in the Mideast|url=http://www.c-span.org/Events/Foreign-Policy-Experts-Examine-Democracies-in-the-Mideast/10737436364/|publisher=C-SPAN|accessdate=14 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609131835/http://www.c-span.org/Events/Foreign-Policy-Experts-Examine-Democracies-in-the-Mideast/10737436364/|archive-date=2013-06-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=AP>{{cite news|last=Flaccus|first=Gillian|title=2 of 4 terror suspects were new Islamic converts|url=http://www.nwherald.com/2012/11/22/2-of-4-terror-suspects-were-new-islamic-converts/awq89hd/|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=The Associated Press|date=November 22, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607222422/http://www.nwherald.com/2012/11/22/2-of-4-terror-suspects-were-new-islamic-converts/awq89hd/|archive-date=2013-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref> [[War hawk|hawkish]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/25/white-house-blindsided-by-iranian-foreign-minister-zarifs-g7-appearance.html |title=white house blindsided by iranian foreign minister zarif's appearance |last=Lee |first=Carol |publisher=cnbc.com |accessdate=2019-09-20 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920222612/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/25/white-house-blindsided-by-iranian-foreign-minister-zarifs-g7-appearance.html |archive-date=2019-09-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How Trump trips up his own Afghanistan peace efforts|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/16/trump-afghanistan-peace-1668390|last=Wilson|first=Mark|publisher=politico.com|accessdate=2019-09-20|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914100424/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/16/trump-afghanistan-peace-1668390|archive-date=2019-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/13/us/politics/mark-dubowitz-iran-deal.html|title=He Was a Tireless Critic of the Iran Deal. Now He Insists He Wanted to Save It.|date=2018-05-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514144653/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/13/us/politics/mark-dubowitz-iran-deal.html|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/08/mcmaster-white-house-danger-to-the-constitution-1418268|title=McMaster blasts former colleagues as 'danger to the Constitution'|last=Morgan|first=Wesley|date=May 9, 2019|website=Politico}}</ref> and [[neoconservative]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Peter|title=Obama's new head boy|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-politics/9891755/Obamas-new-head-boy.html|accessdate=12 March 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph (UK)|date=February 24, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228034030/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-politics/9891755/Obamas-new-head-boy.html|archive-date=2013-02-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"amconserv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/most-favored-democracy/|title=Most Favored Democracy|publisher=The American Conservative|accessdate=2013-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424215942/http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/most-favored-democracy/|archive-date=2013-04-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=csmonitor>{{cite news|last=Jonsson|first=Patrik|title=Shooting of two soldiers in Little Rock puts focus on 'lone wolf' Islamic extremists|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2009/0611/p02s01-usju.html|accessdate=13 March 2013|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=June 11, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130406031548/http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2009/0611/p02s01-usju.html|archive-date=2013-04-06|url-status=live}}</ref> FDD holds events throughout the year, including its annual Washington Forum, briefings on Capitol Hill, expert roundtables for public officials, diplomats, and military officers, book releases, and panel discussions and debates within the policy community. Clifford D. May is FDD\u2019s founder and president. Mark Dubowitz serves as FDD\u00b4s CEO.\n\nFDD has been identified as part of the [[Israel lobby in the United States]] by several scholarly sources.<ref>For example, see the following sources:\n*{{citation|first=Muhammad Idrees|last=Ahmad|title=Road to Iraq: The Making of a Neoconservative War|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780748693054|page=179|quote=The [Israel] lobby has insulated itself with a network of satellite institutions and alliances all invested in cultivating the view that Israeli and US interests are identical... It consists of... think thanks such as WINEP, JINSA, AEI, CSP, the Saban Center for Middle East Policy, FDD, and the defence/national security programmes of the Hudson Institute and the Heritage Foundation...}}\n*{{citation|first1=Ofira|last1=Seliktar|first2=Farhad|last2=Rezaei|title=Iran, Israel, and the United States: The Politics of Counter-Proliferation Intelligence|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2018|isbn=9781498569767|page=168|quote=The Israel lobby stalwarts\u2014the WINEP, the FDD, the Israel Project, the Jewish National Security Affairs (JINSA), CSP, and UANI, among others\u2014produced a considerable number of reports, policy papers, articles, and op-eds, and their reprasantatives regularly testified before Congress.}}\n*{{citation|last1=Mearsheimer|first1=John J.|last2=Stephen|first2=Walt|title=The Israel Lobby and U.S. Foreign Policy|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|location=New York|year=2007|pages=128\u2013130|isbn=978-0-374-17772-0|quote=The [Israel] lobby's drift to the right has been reinforced by the emergence of the neoconservatives... The think tanks and advocacy groups most closely associated with these neoconservatives are the American Enterprise Institute (AEI), the Center for Security Policy (CSP), the Hudson Institute, the Foundation for Defense of Democracies (FDD), the Jewish Institute for National Security Affairs (JINSA), the Middle East Forum (MEF), the Project for a New American Century (PNAC), and the Washington Institute for Near East Policy (WINEP). Virtually all neoconservatives are strongly committed to Israel, a point they emphasize openly and unapologetically.}}\n*{{citation|first=Sujata|last=Ashwarya|title=India-Iran Relations: Progress, Problems and Prospects|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=9781351987073|page=179|quote=In a 155-page report \u201cUS Non-proliferation Strategy for the Changing Middle East,\u201d co-authored by the head of a right-wing pro-Israel lobby group, the Foundation for Defence of Democracies (FDD), Mark Dubowitz, states that...}}</ref>\n== Funding ==\n=== 2001\u20132004 ===\nIn 2011, news website ''[[ThinkProgress]]'' published FDD's [[Form 990]] documents<ref>{{cite web|url=http://d35brb9zkkbdsd.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/FDDdonors.pdf|title=Form 990|publisher=ThinkProgress|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205160813/http://d35brb9zkkbdsd.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/FDDdonors.pdf|archive-date=2014-12-05|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> that revealed where FDD funding came from, from 2001 to 2004. Top donors included:\n*[[Roland Arnall]]: $1,802,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Edgar Bronfman, Sr.|Edgar M.]] and [[Charles Bronfman]]: $1,050,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Michael Steinhardt]]: $850,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n* Abramson Family Foundation (of [[Leonard Abramson]]): $822,523<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Bernard Marcus]]: $600,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Lewis Ranieri]]: $350,000<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\nOther notable donors who gave lesser money during the same period were:\n*[[Haim Saban]]<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Jennifer Laszlo Mizrahi]]<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n*[[Douglas J. Feith]]<ref name=\"thinkprogress\" />\n\n=== 2008\u20132011 ===\nFDD's [[IRS tax forms#Schedules|Schedule A]] documents filed by the end of the 2011 tax year, indicates that the organization from 2008 to 2011 was funded more than $20,000,000,<ref name=\"Salon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.salon.com/2013/08/05/home_depot_founder\u2019s_quiet_10_million_right_wing_investment/|title=Home Depot founder's quiet $10 million right-wing investment|author=Eli Clifton|date=2013-06-08|access-date=2019-02-07|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126101741/https://www.salon.com/2013/08/05/home_depot_founder%E2%80%99s_quiet_10_million_right_wing_investment/|archive-date=2019-01-26|work=Salon}}</ref> and the top three donors were:\n*[[Bernard Marcus]]: $10,745,000<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n*[[Paul Singer (businessman)|Paul Singer]]: $3,600,000<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n*[[Sheldon Adelson]]: $1,510,059<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n=== 2017 ===\nIn 2018, [[Associated Press|AP]] reported that the [[United Arab Emirates]] has wired $2,500,000 to the FDD through [[Elliott Broidy]] and [[George Nader (businessman)|George Nader]], to host a conference amidst [[Qatar diplomatic crisis]] about the country's role as a state-sponsor of terrorism.<ref name=\"AP2018\"/> FDD stated that it does not accept money from foreign governments, adding that \"[a]s is our funding policy, we asked if his funding was connected to any foreign governments or if he had business contracts in the Gulf. He assured us that he did not\".<ref name=\"AP2018\">{{citation|first1=Desmond|last1=Butler|first2=Tom|last2=LoBianco|first3=Bradley|last3=Klapper|first4=Chad|last4=Day|first5=Richard|last5=Lardner|url=https://apnews.com/2e2f7f54c93e4427ad40f3b6cb95d6b1|title=Witness in Mueller probe aided UAE agenda in Congress|work=The Associated Press|access-date=10 January 2020|date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Adam Hanieh]] states that the FDD high-profile conference of 23 May 2017 was in line with UAE's policy at the time, which officially alleged that Qatar finances Islamist groups, adding that emails leaked shortly after show that UAE's Ambassador [[Yousef Al Otaiba]] had a \"cosy relationship\" with the FDD, and had reviewed the remarks made by [[Robert Gates]] at the convention.<ref>{{citation|first=Adam|last=Hanieh|title=Money, Markets, and Monarchies: The Gulf Cooperation Council and the Political Economy of the Contemporary Middle East|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2018|isbn=9781108429146|page=247}}</ref>\n\n=== Others ===\nAdditionally, it is known that as of 2016, FDD has received donations from the following institutions:\n{{Col-begin}}{{Col-break}}\n* Abstraction Fund<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\">{{citation|first1=David|last1=Cronin|first2=Sarah|last2=Marusek|first3=David|last3=Miller|title=The Israel Lobby and the European Union|url=https://purehost.bath.ac.uk/ws/portalfiles/portal/167838098/PII_IsraelLobbyEUreport2016_Cronin_Marusek_Miller.pdf|year=2016|location=Glasgow|publisher=Public Interest Investigations|isbn=978-0-9570274-7-3|via=University of Bath}}</ref>{{rp|24}}\n* [[Roger Hertog#Philanthropy|Hertog Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|24}}\n* Jacobson Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* [[Seth Klarman#Philanthropy|Klarman Family Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* [[Koret Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* [[Milstein Family Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* Nathan Seter Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|30}}\n* Newton and Rochelle Becker Charitable Trust<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|31}}\n{{Col-break}}\n* [[Ed Snider#Nonprofit organizations|Snider Foundation]]<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|31}}\n* Hochberg Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|39}}\n* Marcus Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|39}}\n* Bodman Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|39}}\n* Emerson Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|41}}\n* Eris & Larry Field Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|41}}\n* Rita & Irwin Hochberg Family Foundation<ref name=\"Cronin, Marusek and Miller\"/>{{rp|42}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Activities==\n===The Iran Project===\nIran's government officially threatened FDD and its CEO Mark Dubowitz, enacting sanctions against the CEO, and implicitly threatening the think tank with force from the Iranian state's \"security apparatus,\" as implied in Tehran's own official announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.mehrnews.com/news/149247/Iran-sanctions-Washington-based-FDD-for-role-in-intensifying|title=Iran sanctions Washington-based FDD for role in intensifying 'US economic terrorism'|date=2019-08-24|website=Mehr News Agency|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://en.mfa.ir/portal/newsview/50334| title=Foreign Ministry Blacklists 'Foundation for Defence of Democracies'| date=August 24, 2019| publisher=Islamic Republic of Iran: Ministry of Foreign Affairs}}</ref>\n\nLed by CEO<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fdd.org/team/mark-dubowitz/|title=FDD {{!}} Mark Dubowitz|website=FDD|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130110307/https://www.fdd.org/team/mark-dubowitz/|archive-date=2019-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mark Dubowitz]], FDD's [[Iran]] Program<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fdd.org/projects/iran-program/|title=FDD {{!}} Iran Program|website=FDD|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130110532/https://www.fdd.org/projects/iran-program/|archive-date=2019-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref> seeks to \"address the threat posed by the Islamic Republic of Iran to America and its allies, FDD conducts detailed research, develops actionable and comprehensive policy options, and appears regularly in media.\" <ref name=\":0\" /> FDD says it does this through attacking Iran's \"most vulnerable points: its worldwide media operations, its standing in the United States and Europe, its finances, and its efforts to support terrorist activities abroad\".<ref name=Iran>{{cite web|title=Iran Research|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826113320/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran/|archive-date=2012-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref> Specifically, FDD concerns itself with Iran's nuclear ambitions through its Iran Energy Project<ref name=\"Iran Energy Project\">{{cite web|title=Iran Energy Project|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-energy-project/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316225301/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-energy-project/|archive-date=2013-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref> and Iran's [[Human rights in Iran|human rights abuses]] through its Iran Human Rights Project.<ref name=\"Human Rights Project\">{{cite web|title=Iran Human Rights Project|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-human-rights-project/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317061125/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/iran-human-rights-project/|archive-date=17 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, FDD founded the Iran Energy Project which \"conducts extensive research on ways to deny the Iranian regime the profits of [[Energy in Iran|its energy sector]]\".<ref name=\"Iran Sanctions\">{{cite web|title=Iran - Energy|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran-sanctions/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121185544/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/issues/iran-sanctions/|archive-date=2013-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' credited FDD with bringing \"the idea of gasoline sanctions to political attention.\"<ref name=\"WSJ Iran sanctions\">{{cite news|last=Editorial|title=Pain Iran Can Believe In|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793752240531921|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=2009-03-25|access-date=2017-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010125257/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793752240531921|archive-date=2017-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref> FDD's bi-partisan approach to advocating sanctions legislation has earned praise from Congressmen in both parties. Congressman [[Howard Berman]] (D-CA) thanked the organization saying \"FDD has been one the most committed and creative voices in Washington regarding the Iran nuclear issue and specifically [[Sanctions against Iran|Iran sanctions]]\".<ref name=Berman>{{cite web|title=Remarks by Rep. Howard Berman (D-CA)|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/remarks-by-rep-howard-berman-d-ca/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=29 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529173053/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/remarks-by-rep-howard-berman-d-ca/|archive-date=29 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> FDD's efforts to target the Iranian regime's finances has gone beyond energy sanctions. The organization pushed for sanctions against the [[Central Bank of the Islamic Republic of Iran]] and its use of [[Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication]] (SWIFT) to perform transactions. According to ''The Wall Street Journal'', FDD \"has done most of the spadework on the issue\".<ref name=\"WSJ Swift\">{{cite news|last=Editorial|title=Swift Sanctions on Iran|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203718504577178902535754464|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=February 1, 2012|access-date=2017-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010125327/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203718504577178902535754464|archive-date=2017-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===FDD's Long War Journal===\n[[FDD's Long War Journal]] is a FDD project dedicated to reporting the [[Global War on Terror]] launched by the United States and its allies following the attacks of September 11, 2001. Under the direction of FDD senior fellows [[Bill Roggio]] and Thomas Joscelyn, this website covers stories about countries such as [[Afghanistan]], [[Pakistan]], [[Somalia]], [[Syria]], and [[Iraq]] and follows the actions of [[al Qaeda]] and its affiliates.<ref name=\"LWJ about\">{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/about.php|publisher=The Long War Journal|accessdate=30 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201031735/http://www.longwarjournal.org/about.php|archive-date=2013-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'', \"Roggio's greatest service, then, may be the way he picks up where the mainstream press leaves off, giving readers a simultaneously more specific and holistic understanding of the battlefield\".<ref name=CJR>{{cite news|last=Mcleary|first=Paul|title=Blogging the long war: Bill Roggio wants to be your source for conflict coverage|url=http://www.cjr.org/profile/blogging_the_long_war_1.php|newspaper=Columbia Journalism Review|date=March\u2013April 2008}}</ref>\n\n===The Syria Project===\nFor years, [[Syria]] has been a focus of FDD's research because of its alignment with Iran and support for organizations such as [[Hezbollah]].<ref name=\"Syria NOW\">{{cite web|last=Badran|first=Tony|title=A Syria in minor key|url=https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/commentaryanalysis/a_syria_in_minor_key|publisher=NOW Lebanon|accessdate=31 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118200359/https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/commentaryanalysis/a_syria_in_minor_key|archive-date=2013-01-18|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, as the [[Arab Spring]] spread to Syria, FDD launched \"The Syria Project\" to support dissident efforts in removing the Assad regime.<ref name=\"Syria Project\">{{cite web|title=The Syria Project|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/the-syria-project/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=31 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141124172024/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/project/the-syria-project/|archive-date=2014-11-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In that effort, FDD facilitated a Skype call between dissidents and U.S. journalists in 2012<ref name=\"CNN Skype\">{{cite news|last=Zuka|first=Muhammad|title=A Syrian resistance leader's plea to the world|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/02/16/opinion/zuka-syria-resistance-leader/index.html|newspaper=CNN|date=February 12, 2012|access-date=2013-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827094442/http://www.cnn.com/2012/02/16/opinion/zuka-syria-resistance-leader/index.html|archive-date=2012-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref> and produced multiple studies and memos urging U.S. officials to act.<ref name=Milestones>{{cite web|title=Project Milestones|url=http://www.defenddemocracy.org/action-taken/|publisher=Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=31 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602090127/http://www.defenddemocracy.org/action-taken/|archive-date=2 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nThe [[International Relations Center]] features a report on the foundation on its \"Right Web\" website, a program of the [[Centre-left politics|left of center]]<ref>{{cite web|work=Transnational Institute|publisher=Transnational Institute|title=Left-wing thinkers|last=Blumenthal|first=Sidney|authorlink=Sidney Blumenthal|date=July 30, 1986|url=http://tni.org/archives/media_ips-wp1986|accessdate=2010-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607163250/http://www.tni.org//archives/media_ips-wp1986|archive-date=2011-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=CBC Radio Canada|title=Review: Discussion on The Current about minimum wages and executive compensation, January 29, 2007|date=June 14, 2007|url=http://www.cbc.ca/ombudsman/ombudsmanweb/41.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723003655/http://www.cbc.ca/ombudsman/ombudsmanweb/41.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 23, 2012|accessdate=2010-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Fairness & Accuracy in Reporting|publisher=FAIR|title=Heritage Clones in the Heartland|last=Soley|first=Lawrence|date=September\u2013October 1998|url=http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1430|accessdate=2010-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107203209/http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1430|archive-date=2010-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=FrontPageMagazine|publisher=FrontPageMagazine|title=The ABC's of Media Bias|last=Ponte|first=Lowell|date=October 14, 2004|url=http://97.74.65.51/readArticle.aspx?ARTID=10987|accessdate=2010-11-04}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> think tank [[Institute for Policy Studies]]<ref>{{cite web|title=About Right Web|url=http://rightweb.irc-online.org/about/|publisher=RightWeb|access-date=2013-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121194542/http://rightweb.irc-online.org/about/|archive-date=2013-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref> which, according to its mission statement, seeks to \"check the [[Militarism|militaristic]] drift of the country\". The report states that \"although the FDD is an ardent critic of terrorism, it has not criticized actions taken by Israel against Palestinians that arguably fall into this category\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rightweb.irc-online.org/profile/Foundation_for_Defense_of_Democracies |title=Foundation for Defense of Democracies - Profile - Right Web - Institute for Policy Studies |publisher=Rightweb.irc-online.org |accessdate=2011-08-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105015114/http://www.rightweb.irc-online.org/profile/Foundation_for_Defense_of_Democracies |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref>\n\nThe left-leaning political blog ''[[ThinkProgress]]'' has criticized FDD for \"alarmist rhetoric and fear mongering\",<ref name=thinkprogress>{{cite news|last1=Clifton|first1=Eli|title=EXCLUSIVE: Documents Shed Light On Those Underwriting The Foundation For Defense Of Democracies|url=http://thinkprogress.org/security/2011/07/19/271431/fdd-donors/|work=ThinkProgress|date=19 July 2011|access-date=2014-11-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106221421/http://thinkprogress.org/security/2011/07/19/271431/fdd-donors/|archive-date=2014-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=Your WP:Partisan source|date=August 2016}} for example in April 2002 when they aired a 30-second [[television ad]] campaign called \"Suicide Strategy\" that was described by critics as \"conflating\" Palestinian leader [[Yasser Arafat]] with the likes of [[Osama bin Laden]] and [[Saddam Hussein]]. As FDD explained it: \"a militant [[Islamic terrorism|Islamic terrorist]] who 'martyrs' himself by [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacking a plane]] and flying it into the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]]\"\u2014i.e., the [[September&nbsp;11 attacks]]\u2014\"is no different from a militant Islamic terrorist who 'martyrs' himself by [[Suicide attack|strapping explosives to his body and walking into a hotel]]\"\u2014i.e., [[List of Palestinian suicide attacks|Palestinian suicide attacks]].\n\n==Select publications ==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [http://www.defenddemocracy.org/content/uploads/documents/Small_arms_Report.pdf \"The Tactical and Strategic Use of Small Arms by Terrorists\"], Daveed Gartenstein-Ross and Daniel Trombly, October 2012.\n* \"Terror in the Peaceable Kingdom: Understanding and Addressing Violent Extremism in Canada\", Daveed Gartenstein-Ross and Senator [[Linda Frum]], July 2012.\n* \"Facebook Fatwa: Saudi Clerics, Wahhabi Islam and Social Media\", Jonathan Schanzer and Steven Miller, May 2012.\n* ''The Pasdaran: Inside Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps'', Emanuele Ottolenghi, 2011.\n* ''Palestinian Pulse: What Policymakers Can Learn From Palestinian Social Media'', Jonathan Schanzer and Mark Dubowitz, 2010.\n* ''The Afghanistan-Pakistan Theater: Militant Islam, Security & Stability'', Clifford D. May and Daveed Gartenstein-Ross, 2010.\n* ''From Energy Crisis to Energy Security'', Clifford D. May and Daveed Gartenstein-Ross, 2008.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.defenddemocracy.org/ Official website] \n{{Neoconservatism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foundation For Defense Of Democracies}}\n[[Category:Think tanks established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Foundations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Neoconservatism]]\n[[Category:Conservative organizations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Pahlevun", "label": "safe", "comment": "space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foundation_for_Defense_of_Democracies"}
{"title_page": "Jaguarundi", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jaguarundi\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |author=Caso, A. |author2=de Oliveira, T. |author3=Carvajal, S.V. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T9948A50653167 |year=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Herpailurus yagouaroundi Jaguarundi ZOO D\u011b\u010d\u00edn.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[Nikolai Severtzov|Severtzov]], 1858\n| taxon = Herpailurus yagouaroundi\n| authority = ([[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire|Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]], 1803)\n| synonyms = \n{{collapsible list |bullets=true\n |''Felis yagouaroundi'' <small>Geoffroy, 1803</small>\n |''Puma yaguaroundi''  <small>Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1809</small>\n |''F. eyra'' <small>Fischer, 1814</small>\n |''F. unicolor'' <small>Thraill, 1819</small>\n |''F. cacomitli'' <small>Berlandier, 1859</small>\n |''F. apache'' <small>[[Edgar Alexander Mearns|Mearns]], 1901</small>\n |''F. fossata'' <small>Mearns, 1901</small>\n |''F. panamensis'' <small>[[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1904</small>\n}}\n| range_map =Jaguarundi distribution.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of the jaguarundi (2015)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''jaguarundi''' (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'') ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) is a wild [[felidae|cat]] native to the Americas. Its range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the [[Andes]]. The jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats (such as the small, spotted cats in the [[genus]] ''[[Leopardus]]'') in its external appearance. In fact, the jaguarundi shows several features seen in [[mustelid]]s (such as [[otter]]s and [[weasel]]s)\u2014it has an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. There are two color [[Morph (zoology)|morph]]s\u2014gray and red.\n\nSecretive and alert, the jaguarundi is typically solitary or forms pairs in the wild, though captive individuals are gregarious. Unlike other [[Sympatry|sympatric]] cats such as [[ocelot]]s, the jaguarundi is more active during the day and hunts mainly during daytime and evening hours. Individuals live in large [[home range]]s, and are sparsely distributed within a region. Though an efficient climber and swimmer, the jaguarundi typically prefers hunting on ground. It feeds on various kinds of prey, especially ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Mating occurs throughout the year, with peaks at different times of the year across the range. After a [[gestation period]] of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens. Lifespan of up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.\n\nJaguarundis occur in a broad array of closed as well as open habitats ranging from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. While they are fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela, jaguarundis may have gone [[extinct]] in the US. The [[IUCN]] lists the jaguarundi as [[Least Concern]], but populations are in decline in many parts of its range due to loss and [[Habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] of their habitat and persecution for killing poultry.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe common name \"jaguarundi\" ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) comes from the [[Guarani language|Old Guarani]] word ''yaguarundi'', similar to the [[Old Tupi]] word ''yawaum'di''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferreira |first=A.B.H. |year=1986 |title=Novo Dicion\u00e1rio da L\u00edngua Portuguesa|language=Portuguese |trans-title=New Dictionary of the Portuguese Language |edition=2nd|place=Rio de Janeiro |publisher=Nova Fronteira |page=980}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|jaguarundi|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> In some [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the jaguarundi is also called ''gato colorado'', ''gato moro'', ''le\u00f3n brenero'', ''leoncillo'' and ''tigrillo''.<ref name=iucn/> It is also called ''eyra'', ''gato-mourisco'', ''gato-preto'', ''gato-vermelho'' and ''maracaj\u00e1-preto'' in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=de Miranda |first1=E.E. |last2=Gambarini |first2=A. |title=Natureza, Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o e Cultura: Ensaio sobre a Rela\u00e7\u00e3o do Homem com a Natureza no Brasil |trans-title=Nature, Conservation and Culture: Essay on the Relationship between Man and Nature in Brazil |date=2003 |publisher=Metalivros |location=S\u00e3o Paulo |isbn=9788585371470 |page=113 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Nowell |editor1-first=K. |editor2-last=Jackson |editor2-first=P. |editor3-last=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |date=1996 |publisher=IUCN |location=Gland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |page=146}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis yagouarundi'' was the [[scientific name]] used by [[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]] in 1803 who described two [[zoological specimen|specimen]]s from Central America, including one from [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, \u00c9. |authorlink=\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire |year=1803 |title=Catalogue des Mammif\u00e8res du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |trans-title=Catalogue of Mammals of the National Museum of Natural History| language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |page=124 |chapter=Le chat yagouarundi. ''Felis yagouarundi'' (The cat jaguarundi: ''Felis yagouarundi'')|chapter-url={{Google Books|id=951AAAAAcAAJ|page=124|plainurl=yes}} }}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several more specimens, presumably jaguarundis, were described:\n*''Felis eyra'' proposed by [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim]] in 1814 was a [[rust (color)|ferruginous]] skin from [[Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Fischer von Waldheim, G. |authorlink=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim |year=1814 |title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata : in usum praelectionum Academiae imperialis medico-chirugicae mosquensis edita |language=Latin |location=Moscow |publisher=Nicolai S. Vsevolozsky |page=228 |chapter=''Felis eyra'' |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc/page/228}}</ref>\n*[[Gulf Coast Jaguarundi|''F. cacomitli'']] proposed by [[Jean-Louis Berlandier]] in 1859 was a skull and a grayish skin of a female from the [[Rio Grande]] area in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Berlandier, J.-L. |authorlink=Jean-Louis Berlandier |year=1859 |title=Report on the United States and Mexican boundary survey made under the direction of the Secretary of the Interior |volume=II. Mammals of the boundary |editor1=Baird, S. F. |location=Washington |publisher=A.O.P. Nicholson |pages=12\u201313 |chapter=''Felis yagouarundi'' (Desm.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKogAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA12#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi tolteca'' proposed by [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1898 was a skull and a reddish skin from [[Sinaloa]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas |year=1898 |title=On new mammals from Western Mexico and Lower California |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=7 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201346 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof711898lond/page/40}}</ref>\n*''F. ameghinoi'' proposed by [[Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg]] in 1898 for bones, presumably of a jaguarundi, found near [[San Luis, Argentina]], which are embalmed in the [[Turin Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Holmberg, E. L. |authorlink=Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg |year=1898 |chapter=La fauna de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina (The fauna of the Argentine Republic) |pages=477\u2013602 |title=Segundo Censo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina Mayo 10 de 1895 |trans-title=Second Census of the Argentine Republic May 10, 1895 |volume=1 |editor=Carrasco, G. |publisher=Taller Tipogr\u00e1fico de la Penitenciar\u00eda Nacional |location=Buenos Aires }}</ref>\n*''F. fossata'' by [[Edgar Alexander Mearns]] in 1901 was a large skull from [[Yucat\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mearns, E.A. |authorlink=Edgar Alexander Mearns |year=1901 |title=Two new cats of the eyra group from North America |volume=14 |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |pages=149\u2013151 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio14biol/page/148}}</ref>\n*''F. panamensis'' by [[Joel Asaph Allen]] in 1904 was a dusky gray skin of a young adult female collected in Panama's [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J.A. |authorlink=Joel Asaph Allen |year=1904 |title=Mammals from southern Mexico and Central and South America |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=29\u201380 |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/662//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/bul/B020a04.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi melantho'' by Oldfield Thomas in 1914 were skulls and blackish brown skins of a male and a female from [[Pozuzo District|Pozuzu]] in Peru.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1914 |title=On various South-American mammals |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=13 |issue=75 |pages=345\u2013363 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof1319unse/page/350}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Genus (biology)|generic]] name ''Herpailurus'' was proposed by [[Nikolai Severtzov]] in 1858 for the jaguarundi.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Severtzov |first1=N.A. |authorlink=Nikolai Severtzov |year=1858 |title=Notice sur la classification multis\u00e9riale des carnivores, sp\u00e9cialement des F\u00e9lid\u00e9s, et les \u00e9tudes de zoologie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale qui s'y rattachent |trans-title=Notes on the classification of the carnivores, especially the Felidae, and the respective zoological studies |journal=Revue et Magasin de Zoologie Pure et Appliqu\u00e9e |volume=X |language=French| pages=385\u2013396 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revueetmagasinde10soci#page/390/mode/2up}}</ref> Later authors classified the jaguarundi in the genus ''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]'' along with the [[cougar]] (''P. concolor'').<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000211 |heading=Species ''Puma yagouaroundi'' |page=545}}</ref> In 2017, the [[IUCN]] Cat Specialist Group listed the jaguarundi as a [[monotypic taxon]] of the genus ''Herpailurus''.<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |display-authors=23 |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref> [[Phylogeography|Phylogeographical]] analysis of jaguarundi samples from across its range found no genetic evidence for [[subspecies]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |author2=Pinedo-Castro, M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |pages=245\u2013288 |chapter=Population genetics and phylogeographic analyses of the jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') by means of three mitochondrial markers: The first molecular study of this species |title=Molecular Population Genetics, Evolutionary Biology and Biological Conservation on Neotropical Carnivores |editor1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |editor2=Shostell, J. M. |publisher=Nova Publishers |location=New York |isbn=978-1-62417-079-9 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/230597248_Population_genetics_and_phylogeographic_of_the_jaguarundi_Puma_yaguaroundi_by_means_of_three_mitochondrial_markers_the_first_molecular_population_study_of_this_species_Chapter_8_Molecular_Population_G}}</ref>\n\n==Phylogeny and evolution==\n{{cladogram|title=\n|align=left\n|caption=The ''Puma'' lineage of the family [[Felidae]], depicted along with closely related genera.<ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W.E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae) |year=2010 |pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142 |editor1-last=Macdonald |editor1-first=D.W. |editor2-last=Loveridge |editor2-first=A.J. |title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-19-923445-5 |edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n|1={{clade | style=font-size:90%;line-height:100%;width:450px;\n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |label1=''Lynx'' lineage\n         |1=''[[Lynx (genus)|Lynx]]''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{clade\n            |label1=''Puma'' lineage\n            |1={{clade\n               |label1=''[[Acinonyx]]''\n               |1= ''Acinonyx jubatus'' <br/>([[Cheetah]]) |image1=[[File:Cynailurus guttata - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam - (white background).jpg|80px|left]]\n               |2={{clade\n                  |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n                  |1=''Puma concolor'' <br/>([[Cougar]]) |image1=[[File:Felis concolor - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam -(white background).jpg|70px|left]]\n                  |label2='''''Herpailurus'''''&nbsp;\n                  |2=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' <br/>('''Jaguarundi''')\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=Domestic cat lineage\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''\n            |label2=Leopard cat lineage\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Otocolobus]]''\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n}}\n\nThe jaguarundi is most closely related to the cougar and [[cheetah]].<ref name=\"Culver\">{{cite journal |author1=Culver, M. |author2=Johnson, W. E. |author3=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author4=O'Brien, S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2000 |title=Genomic Ancestry of the American Puma |journal=[[Journal of Heredity]] |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186 |pmid=10833043 |url-status=dead |url=http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616200443/http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> These three species together form the ''Puma'' lineage, one of the eight lineages of Felidae; the ''Puma'' lineage [[Genetic divergence|diverged]] from the rest {{mya|6.7}}. The [[sister group]] of the ''Puma'' lineage is a [[clade]] of smaller [[Old World]] cats that includes the genera ''[[Felis]]'', ''[[Otocolobus]]'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]''.<ref name=\"werdelin\"/> \n\nThe three species of the ''Puma'' lineage may have had a [[common ancestor]] during the [[Miocene]], about {{mya|8.25}}.<ref name=\"adams\">{{cite journal |last1=Adams |first1=D. B. |title=The cheetah: native American |journal=Science |year=1979 |volume=205 |issue=4411 |pages=1155\u20131158 |doi=10.1126/science.205.4411.1155 |pmid=17735054 |bibcode=1979Sci...205.1155A |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6901/86b75e66b681ff0d83772f74068cd1b908b5.pdf}}</ref><ref name=johnson>{{cite journal |pmid=9071018 |year=1997 |last1=Johnson |first1=W. E. |last2=O'Brien |first2=S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Phylogenetic reconstruction of the Felidae using 16S rRNA and NADH-5 mitochondrial genes |volume=44 |issue=S1 |pages=S98\u2013S116 |journal=Journal of Molecular Evolution |doi=10.1007/PL00000060|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232587 |bibcode=1997JMolE..44S..98J}}</ref> ''Acinonyx'' possibly diverged from the lineage in the Americas;<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal |last1=Johnson |first1=W.E. |last2=Eizirik |first2=E. |last3=Pecon-Slattery |first3=J. |last4=Murphy |first4=W.J. |last5=Antunes |first5=A. |last6=Teeling |first6=E. |last7=O'Brien |first7=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |doi=10.1126/science.1122277 |title=The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=311 |pages=73\u201377 |pmid=16400146 |issue=5757 |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1230866}}</ref><ref name=dobrynin>{{cite journal |last1=Dobrynin |first1=P. |last2=Liu |first2=S. |last3=Tamazian |first3 = G. |last4=Xiong |first4=Z. |last5=Yurchenko |first5=A. A. |last6=Krasheninnikova |first6=K. |last7=Kliver |first7=S. |last8=Schmidt-K\u00fcntzel |first8=A. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genomic legacy of the African cheetah, ''Acinonyx jubatus'' |journal=Genome Biology |year=2015 |volume=16 |pages=277 |doi=10.1186/s13059-015-0837-4 |pmid=26653294 |pmc=4676127}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Brien |first1=S. J. |last2=Johnson |first2=W. E. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The evolution of cats |journal=Scientific American |date=2007 |volume=297 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201375 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0707-68 |url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/O%27brien2007EvolutionCats.pdf}}</ref> some authors alternatively suggest that the cheetah diverged in the Old World.<ref>{{cite journal |first=R. |last=Barnett |author2=I. B. |author3=Phillips, M. J. |author4=Martin, L. D. |author5=Harington, C. R. |author6=Leonard, J. A. |author7=Cooper, A. |year=2005 |title=Evolution of the extinct Sabretooths and the American cheetah-like cat |journal=[[Current Biology]] |volume=15 |issue=15 |pages=R589\u2013R590 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2005.07.052 |pmid=16085477}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faurby |first1=S. |last2=Werdelin |first2=L. |last3=Svenning |first3=J. C. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The difference between trivial and scientific names: there were never any true cheetahs in North America |journal=Genome Biology |year=2016 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=89 |doi=10.1186/s13059-016-0943-y|pmid=27150269 |pmc=4858926}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Puma'' lineage appears to have migrated from Asia to North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]], arriving in South America via the [[Isthmus of Panama]] by [[Late Pliocene]] or [[Early Pleistocene]]. This was possibly followed by the bifurcation of the lineage into the cougar and ''Herpailurus'' (represented by ''H. pumoides'') in South America around {{mya|4|3}} between the Late Pliocene and Early Pleistocene. ''H. pumoides'' went extinct around [[Middle Pleistocene]], around the time the modern jaguarundi came into existence; the oldest fossils of the modern jaguarundi date back to the [[Late Pleistocene]] in Brazil around {{mya|0.5}}. The original North American cougars were extripated during the [[Pleistocene extinctions]] around 10,000 years ago; North America was then recolonized by South American cougars and jaguarundis 10,000\u20138,000 years ago.<ref name=bellani/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Culver |first1=M. |title=Genomic ancestry of the American puma (''Puma concolor'') |journal=Journal of Heredity |date=2000 |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chimento |first1=N.R. |last2=Dondas |first2=A. |title=First record of ''Puma concolor'' (Mammalia, Felidae) in the Early-Middle Pleistocene of South America |journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution |date=2017 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=381\u2013389 |doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9385-x}}</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header    = \n| header_align = center\n\n| image1    = Jaguarondi 2.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = <center>Red morph</center>\n\n| image2    = Jaguarundi seitlich.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  = <center>Gray morph</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}} \nThe jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats in its external appearance. This has been attributed to variations in its [[karyotype]]\u2014the jaguarundi has 38 [[chromosome]]s, unlike the 36 in other small South American cats, and the chromosomal features resemble those of Old World cats such as the [[leopard cat]] (''Prionailurus bengalensis'').<ref name=WCoW/> Interestingly, the jaguarundi is characterized by several [[mustelid]] features\u2014an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. As such, the jaguarundi is sometimes considered similar to [[marten]]s, [[otter]]s or [[weasel]]s.<ref name=\"bellani\">{{cite book |last1=Bellani |first1=G.G. |title=Felines of the World: Discoveries in Taxonomic Classification and History |date=2020 |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-12-816503-4 |pages=223-231 |url={{Google Books|id=xK2wDwAAQBAJ|page=223|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|page=818|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=818|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The head-and-body length is between {{convert|53|and|77|cm|in|abbr=on}}; the strong, muscular tail is {{convert|31|\u2013|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though larger individuals weighing around {{convert|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}} have been reported.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |author1=Sunquist, M. |author2=Sunquist, F. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild Cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |pages=113\u2013119 |isbn= 978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/113}}</ref><ref name=\"fws.gov\">{{Cite journal |author1=Brown, D.E. |author2=Gonzalez, C.A. |year=1999 |title=Jaguarundi (''Felis yagouaroundi tolteca'') |url=http://www.fws.gov/southwest/es/Arizona/Documents/Redbook/Jaguarundi%20RB.pdf |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |issue=32 |pages=155\u2013157}}</ref> Males are slightly larger than females.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nThe coat is uniformly colored with at most a few faint markings on the face and the belly, though kittens may be spotted for a short duration. Black and white marks on the lips and the snout, similar to those of the cougar, can be clearly seen in juveniles and some adults. The fur color varies from blackish to brownish-grey with a grizzled look due to alternating bright and dark rings on individual hairs (called gray [[Morph (biology)|morph]]), to foxy red to chestnut (called red morph); earlier these morphs were considered two different species. Individuals of both colors can be born in the same litter.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=\"hildyard\">{{cite book |last1=Sirimarco |first1=E. |editor1-last=Hildyard |editor1-first=A. |title=Endangered Wildlife and Plants of the World (Volume 6) |date=2001 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Co |location=New York |isbn=0-7614-7200-2 |pages=736-738 |chapterurl={{Google Books|plainurl=yes|id=5YYqd4ROFfkC|page=736}} |chapter=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yaguarondi cacomitli'')}}</ref> Blackish brown individuals superficially resemble the [[tayra]] (''Eira barbara''), but the latter can be told apart by the clear, yellowish patch on the throat.<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite journal |last1=de Oliveira |first1=T.G. |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |journal=Mammalian Species |date=1998 |issue=578 |pages=1-6 |doi=10.2307/3504500 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275737351_Herpailurus_yagouaroundi}}</ref> The red morph is seen more often in dry, open areas. [[Melanism|melanistic]] individuals have been reported, but they are not completely black; the head and the throat are clearly paler than the rest of the body.<ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=152\u2013156|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=152|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref>  The ears, {{convert|2.5|\u2013|4|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, are widely spaced and, unlike many other felids, lack white spots on the back.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos>{{cite book |author1-last=Aranda |author1-first=M. |author2-last=Caso |author2-first=A. |editor1-last=Ceballos |editor1-first=G. |title=Mammals of Mexico |publisher=John Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-1-4214-0879-8 |pages=498-499 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl={{Google Books|page=498|plainurl=yes|id=UrvxBQAAQBAJ}}}}</ref> The jaguarundi has a total of 30 teeth; the [[dental formula]] is {{DentalFormula|upper=3.1.3.1|lower=3.1.2.1}}.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nAmong felids, the jaguarundi is closely similar to the [[flat-headed cat]] (''Prionailurus planiceps''), but has a longer body and proportionately longer legs, is heavier and lacks the dark markings on the cheeks of the flat-headed cat.<ref name=ms/> Tawny jaguarundis bear a similar coloration as the signficantly larger cougar.<ref name=Hunter/>\n\n==Behavior and ecology==\n[[File:Jaguarondi 1.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are good climbers and can easily walk on branches.]]\nThe jaguarundi is shy and reclusive, and apparently very cautious of [[Animal trapping|traps]].<ref name=Simberloff/> There have been only a few [[radio telemetry]] studies of jaguarundis in Belize, Brazil and Mexico.<ref name=Hunter/> Though activity has been observed throughout the day and at night, jaguarundis seem to prefer hunting during daytime and evening hours; a study in Belize reported that jaguarundis started moving before dawn and remained active through most of the day till sunset with a peak in hunting from late morning to noon.<ref name=ms/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Konecny |first1=M.J. |title=Movement patterns and food habits of four sympatric carnivore species in Belize, South America |journal=Advances in Neotropical Mammalogy |date=1989 |pages=243-264 |url=http://library.bfreebz.org/Mammals/Michael%20Konecny,%20Movement%20Patterns%20and%20Food%20Habits%20of%20Four%20Sympatric%20Carnivore%20Species%20in%20Belize,%20Central%20America,%201989.pdf}}</ref> The cat appears to be more [[Diurnality|diurnal]] than most other cats, especially spotted cats that tend to be more active at night.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=WCoW/> The jaguarundi can swim across medium-sized rivers; an individual was recorded swimming across the [[Tuichi River]] (Bolivia).<ref name=Hunter/> Jaguarundis are efficient climbers as well, but hunt mainly on ground; its coat color works as a good camouflage for terrestrial activity.<ref name=Nowak/> They can leap up to {{convert|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} into the air to catch birds.<ref name=WCoW/> Predators recorded for jaguarundis include [[boa constrictor]]s, cougars and [[domestic dog]]s.<ref name=Hunter/> Parasites such as [[hookworm]]s (''[[Ancylostoma]]'' species), [[tapeworm]]s (such as  ''[[Spirometra]]'' and ''[[Toxocara]]'' species) and the [[lung fluke]] have been found in jaguarundis.<ref name=ms/>\n\nStudies have mostly observed jaguarundis alone or in pairs; pairs could probably be formed between mothers and older kittens or between individuals of opposite sexes during the mating season. Individuals in captivity have been found to be more gregarious.<ref name=WCoW/> [[Home range]]s tend to be large; a study in Brazil recorded home ranges {{convert|1.4|\u2013|18|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size for females, while those of males measured {{convert|8.5|\u2013|25.3|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in area.<ref name=Hunter/> Two males in Belize were recorded to have exceptionally large home ranges spanning an area of {{convert|88|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} and {{convert|100|sqkm|sqmi}}, while the home range of a female in the same region measured {{convert|13|\u2013|20|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size.<ref name=Nowak/> Population densities are typically low, around {{convert|0.01|to|0.05|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}, though the Llanos in Costa Rica and Venezuela have recorded figures as high as {{convert|0.2|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=bellani/>\n\nMarking behavior could serve as a means of olfactory or visual communication; individuals in captivity have been observed scraping areas with their hind feet (sometimes with urination), clawing on logs, rubbing objects with their heads and leaving feces uncovered. Social behavior such as grooming, growling and sniffing has been recorded. The jaguarundi has a broad vocal repertoire; 13 different calls have been recorded including chattering, purring, screaming, a 'wah-wah' call, whistling, yapping and a peculiar bird-like chirp. In captivity, females in [[estrus]] have been observed making faint sounds as they [[scent mark]] the area around their enclosures.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/> \n\n===Diet===\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi, ZOO Praha 254.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are [[Generalist and specialist species|generalist]] carnivores.]]\nThe jaguarundi typically feed on small-sized prey weighing less than {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, including ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Jaguarundis will also take larger prey such as domestic poultry, fish, [[marmoset]]s, rabbits and [[opossum]]s; a study recorded small deer (possibly [[carrion]]) in the diet. Vegetation such as grasses have also been recorded in their diet.<ref name=Hunter/><ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/><ref name=ms/> A study showed jaguarundis take {{convert|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} vertebrate prey on an average everyday.<ref name=ms/> The broad array of prey recorded for the jaguarundi across its range and varying proportions of different prey in its diet could indicate that the cat tends to feed on the most abundant and easily catchable prey in the area.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nJaguarundis have been observed mating all year round, with peaks at different times of the year across the range; for instance, in Mexico breeding peaks in January and March. Estrus lasts three to five days, marked by the female regularly rolling onto her back and [[spraying urine]]. [[Sexually mature]] males will pursue the female, not reacting to any aggressive behavior from her side. As in many other felids, the male bites the fur on the female's neck on mounting; the female lets out a loud scream on penetration.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/>\n\nAfter a [[gestation]] period of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens in a den constructed in a dense thicket, hollow tree, or similar cover. The kittens are covered well with fur and the underside is marked with spots, which disappear as they age; the coat color gradually changes as the kittens grow older.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/> The mother starts bringing solid food for the kittens when they are around three weeks old, who simply play with it till the mother ingests it; kittens are capable of taking solid food like birds and guinea pigs at around six weeks. Jaguarundis become sexually mature at one to three years of age. Lifespan up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=Nowak/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe jaguarundi inhabits a wide variety of habitats\u2014from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. It can also occur in [[cloud forest]]s, [[mangrove]]s and [[savanna]]s.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=ceballos/> Unlike the [[Sympatry|sympatric]] [[margay]], [[ocelot]] and [[oncilla]], the jaguarundi can occur in open areas as well. In open habitats the jaguarundi prefers areas with vegetative cover such as cacti, which would generally be difficult for possible predators to penetrate; there may be a few clearings at the periphery of such areas. Jaguarundis tend to stay close to a source of running water.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=fws.gov/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Coronado-Quibrera |first1=W.P. |last2=Olmos-Oropeza |first2=G. |last3=Bender |first3=L.C. |last4=Rosas-Rosas |first4=O.C. |last5=Palacio-N\u00fa\u00f1ez |first5=J. |last6=Tarango-Ar\u00e1mbula |first6=L.A. |last7=Herrera-Haro |first7=J.G. |title=Adaptability of the threatened jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Schereber, 1777) to human-altered environments in San Luis Potos\u00ed, Mexico |journal=Acta Zool\u00f3gica Mexicana |date=2019 |volume=35 |pages=1\u201315 |doi=10.21829/azm.2019.3502210 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/310f/6597fd914eb664e160637b4b1b1d57d87fe7.pdf}}</ref> The jaguarundi is noted for its resistance to environmental disturbances in its habitat; it can successfully thrive in reforested areas.<ref name=ceballos/> While commonly inhabiting lowlands up to {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the sea level, this cat has been reported at elevations as high as {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Colombia.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThe range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the Andes\u2014second only to the cougar in the [[Latitude|latitudinal]] extent of its distribution. However, not all parts of its range have been studied well. The jaguarundi is fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela.<ref name=\"rev\">{{cite journal |last1=Giordano |first1=A.J. |title=Ecology and status of the jaguarundi ''Puma yagouaroundi'': a synthesis of existing knowledge |journal=Mammal Review |date=2016 |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201343 |doi=10.1111/mam.12051 |url=https://carnivores.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Giordano_2015_mam12051_Jaguarundi.pdf}}</ref> It is possibly [[extinct]] in the US;<ref name=iucn/> a study in 1999 refuted claims of sightings in Arizona.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=D.E. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez |first2=C.A.L. |title=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Geoffroy 1803) not in Arizona or Sonora |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |date=1999 |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=155-157 |jstor=40021308}}</ref> The last confirmed sighting in the US was probably of a roadkilled individual near [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] (Texas) in 1986.<ref name=rev/>\n\nJaguarundis have been sighted in [[Florida]] since the early 20th century; their presence there is attributed to a writer from [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]] who at some point imported the animals from their native habitat and released them near his hometown and in other locations across the state. Several sightings have been reported since 1907; in 1977 [[W. T. Neill]] noted that the population was declining. Jaguarundis have also been reported in the coastal area of [[Alabama]] since the 1980s, which may be evidence of the Florida population migrating northward.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title=Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida |last1=Simberloff |first1=D. |authorlink=Daniel Simberloff |author2=Schmitz, D.C. |author3=Brown, T.C. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1997 |publisher=Island Press |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-55963-430-4 |url={{Google Books |plainurl=yes|page=172|id=rtrpSllq4SQC}} |pages=172\u2013173}}</ref> The jaguarundi has also been recorded from [[Cerro Largo Department|Cerro Largo]] in [[Uruguay]], where its presence was doubted.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Grattarola, F. |author2=Hernandez, D. |author3=Duarte, A. |author4=Gaucher, L. |author5=Perazza, G. |display-authors=3 |year=2016 |title=Primer registro de yaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) en Uruguay, con comentarios sobre monitereo participativo |journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Zool\u00f3gica del Uruguay |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=85\u221291 |language=Spanish |trans-title=First record of jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) in Uruguay, with comments on participatory monitoring}}</ref>\n\n==Threats and conservation==\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi.jpg|thumb|left|Captive jaguarundi in the Zoo de Pont-Scorff (France)]]\nThe jaguarundi has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2002. Mexican populations, except those in the northeast, appear to be stable. The huge reserves of the [[Amazon Basin]] are probably the only conservation units that can sustain long-term viable populations. In its 2015 revision, the IUCN noted that the species should be listed as [[Near Threatened]], but there was not enough data to go upon to extend this classification throughout the range.<ref name=iucn/> The jaguarundi is not particularly sought after for its fur due to its poor quality and low value, but is suffering decline due to habitat loss.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=fws.gov/> Other threats include risks of [[habitat fragmentation]] and persecution for killing poultry.<ref name=iucn/> The North and Central American populations of the jaguarundi are listed in [[CITES Appendix I]] and all the other populations are listed in [[CITES Appendix II]].<ref name=ceballos/> Populations in the US are protected under the [[Endangered Species Act]];<ref name=MSW3/> the [[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]] has expressed concern that its presence in South Texas may be imperiled due to loss of the cat's native habitat.<ref name=Texas2003>{{cite web |url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/landwater/land/habitats/southtx_plain/endangered_species/ |title=Endangered Species |website=Tpwd.state.tx.us |date=2003-04-15 |access-date=2011-09-15 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Populations in Mexico are listed under the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lorenzo |first1=C. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez-Ruiz |first2=N. |title=Mammals in the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010 |journal=Therya |date=2018 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=69\u201372 |doi=10.12933/therya-18-565 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323250093_Mammals_in_the_Mexican_Official_Norm_NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010}}</ref> Hunting jaguarundi is restricted in Peru and banned in Argentina, Belize, Brazil, Bolivia, Colombia, Costa Rica, French Guiana, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Panama, Paraguay, Suriname, Uruguay, the US and Venezuela.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Acinonychini]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons and category|Puma yagouaroundi|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=93 |title=Jaguarundi ''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |website=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group}}\n* {{cite web |website=Big Cats Online |url=http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031107150747/http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-date=2003-11-07 |df=dmy-all |title=Jaguarundi |series=Wild Cat Species and Distribution \u2013 South America}}\n* {{cite Americana |wstitle=Jaguarondi |short=x}}\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q182304}}\n\n[[Category:Puma (genus)]]\n[[Category:Felids of Central America]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Felids of South America]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Belize]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of French Guiana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Honduras]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Suriname]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Panama]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Peru]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Fauna of northern South America]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1803]]\n[[Category:Guaran\u00ed words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jaguarundi\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |author=Caso, A. |author2=de Oliveira, T. |author3=Carvajal, S.V. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T9948A50653167 |year=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Herpailurus yagouaroundi Jaguarundi ZOO D\u011b\u010d\u00edn.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[Nikolai Severtzov|Severtzov]], 1858\n| taxon = Herpailurus yagouaroundi\n| authority = ([[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire|Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]], 1803)\n| synonyms = \n{{collapsible list |bullets=true\n |''Felis yagouaroundi'' <small>Geoffroy, 1803</small>\n |''Puma yaguaroundi''  <small>Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1809</small>\n |''F. eyra'' <small>Fischer, 1814</small>\n |''F. unicolor'' <small>Thraill, 1819</small>\n |''F. cacomitli'' <small>Berlandier, 1859</small>\n |''F. apache'' <small>[[Edgar Alexander Mearns|Mearns]], 1901</small>\n |''F. fossata'' <small>Mearns, 1901</small>\n |''F. panamensis'' <small>[[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1904</small>\n}}\n| range_map =Jaguarundi distribution.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of the jaguarundi (2015)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''jaguarundi''' (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'') ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) is a wild [[felidae|cat]] native to the Americas. Its range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the [[Andes]]. The jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats (such as the small, spotted cats in the [[genus]] ''[[Leopardus]]'') in its external appearance. In fact, the jaguarundi shows several features seen in [[mustelid]]s (such as [[otter]]s and [[weasel]]s)\u2014it has an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. There are two color [[Morph (zoology)|morph]]s\u2014gray and red.\n\nSecretive and alert, the jaguarundi is typically solitary or forms pairs in the wild, though captive individuals are gregarious. Unlike other [[Sympatry|sympatric]] cats such as [[ocelot]]s, the jaguarundi is more active during the day and hunts mainly during daytime and evening hours. Individuals live in large [[home range]]s, and are sparsely distributed within a region. Though an efficient climber and swimmer, the jaguarundi typically prefers hunting on ground. It feeds on various kinds of prey, especially ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Mating occurs throughout the year, with peaks at different times of the year across the range. After a [[gestation period]] of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens. Lifespan of up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.\n\nJaguarundis occur in a broad array of closed as well as open habitats ranging from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. While they are fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela, jaguarundis may have gone [[extinct]] in the US. The [[IUCN]] lists the jaguarundi as [[Least Concern]], but populations are in decline in many parts of its range due to loss and [[Habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] of their habitat and persecution for killing poultry.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe common name \"jaguarundi\" ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) comes from the [[Guarani language|Old Guarani]] word ''yaguarundi'', similar to the [[Old Tupi]] word ''yawaum'di''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferreira |first=A.B.H. |year=1986 |title=Novo Dicion\u00e1rio da L\u00edngua Portuguesa|language=Portuguese |trans-title=New Dictionary of the Portuguese Language |edition=2nd|place=Rio de Janeiro |publisher=Nova Fronteira |page=980}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|jaguarundi|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> In some [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the jaguarundi is also called ''gato colorado'', ''gato moro'', ''le\u00f3n brenero'', ''leoncillo'' and ''tigrillo''.<ref name=iucn/> It is also called ''eyra'', ''gato-mourisco'', ''gato-preto'', ''gato-vermelho'' and ''maracaj\u00e1-preto'' in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=de Miranda |first1=E.E. |last2=Gambarini |first2=A. |title=Natureza, Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o e Cultura: Ensaio sobre a Rela\u00e7\u00e3o do Homem com a Natureza no Brasil |trans-title=Nature, Conservation and Culture: Essay on the Relationship between Man and Nature in Brazil |date=2003 |publisher=Metalivros |location=S\u00e3o Paulo |isbn=9788585371470 |page=113 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Nowell |editor1-first=K. |editor2-last=Jackson |editor2-first=P. |editor3-last=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |date=1996 |publisher=IUCN |location=Gland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |page=146}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis yagouarundi'' was the [[scientific name]] used by [[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]] in 1803 who described two [[zoological specimen|specimen]]s from Central America, including one from [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, \u00c9. |authorlink=\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire |year=1803 |title=Catalogue des Mammif\u00e8res du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |trans-title=Catalogue of Mammals of the National Museum of Natural History| language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |page=124 |chapter=Le chat yagouarundi. ''Felis yagouarundi'' (The cat jaguarundi: ''Felis yagouarundi'')|chapter-url={{Google Books|id=951AAAAAcAAJ|page=124|plainurl=yes}} }}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several more specimens, presumably jaguarundis, were described:\n*''Felis eyra'' proposed by [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim]] in 1814 was a [[rust (color)|ferruginous]] skin from [[Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Fischer von Waldheim, G. |authorlink=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim |year=1814 |title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata : in usum praelectionum Academiae imperialis medico-chirugicae mosquensis edita |language=Latin |location=Moscow |publisher=Nicolai S. Vsevolozsky |page=228 |chapter=''Felis eyra'' |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc/page/228}}</ref>\n*[[Gulf Coast Jaguarundi|''F. cacomitli'']] proposed by [[Jean-Louis Berlandier]] in 1859 was a skull and a grayish skin of a female from the [[Rio Grande]] area in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Berlandier, J.-L. |authorlink=Jean-Louis Berlandier |year=1859 |title=Report on the United States and Mexican boundary survey made under the direction of the Secretary of the Interior |volume=II. Mammals of the boundary |editor1=Baird, S. F. |location=Washington |publisher=A.O.P. Nicholson |pages=12\u201313 |chapter=''Felis yagouarundi'' (Desm.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKogAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA12#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi tolteca'' proposed by [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1898 was a skull and a reddish skin from [[Sinaloa]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas |year=1898 |title=On new mammals from Western Mexico and Lower California |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=7 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201346 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof711898lond/page/40}}</ref>\n*''F. ameghinoi'' proposed by [[Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg]] in 1898 for bones, presumably of a jaguarundi, found near [[San Luis, Argentina]], which are embalmed in the [[Turin Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Holmberg, E. L. |authorlink=Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg |year=1898 |chapter=La fauna de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina (The fauna of the Argentine Republic) |pages=477\u2013602 |title=Segundo Censo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina Mayo 10 de 1895 |trans-title=Second Census of the Argentine Republic May 10, 1895 |volume=1 |editor=Carrasco, G. |publisher=Taller Tipogr\u00e1fico de la Penitenciar\u00eda Nacional |location=Buenos Aires }}</ref>\n*''F. fossata'' by [[Edgar Alexander Mearns]] in 1901 was a large skull from [[Yucat\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mearns, E.A. |authorlink=Edgar Alexander Mearns |year=1901 |title=Two new cats of the eyra group from North America |volume=14 |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |pages=149\u2013151 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio14biol/page/148}}</ref>\n*''F. panamensis'' by [[Joel Asaph Allen]] in 1904 was a dusky gray skin of a young adult female collected in Panama's [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J.A. |authorlink=Joel Asaph Allen |year=1904 |title=Mammals from southern Mexico and Central and South America |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=29\u201380 |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/662//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/bul/B020a04.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi melantho'' by Oldfield Thomas in 1914 were skulls and blackish brown skins of a male and a female from [[Pozuzo District|Pozuzu]] in Peru.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1914 |title=On various South-American mammals |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=13 |issue=75 |pages=345\u2013363 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof1319unse/page/350}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Genus (biology)|generic]] name ''Herpailurus'' was proposed by [[Nikolai Severtzov]] in 1858 for the jaguarundi.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Severtzov |first1=N.A. |authorlink=Nikolai Severtzov |year=1858 |title=Notice sur la classification multis\u00e9riale des carnivores, sp\u00e9cialement des F\u00e9lid\u00e9s, et les \u00e9tudes de zoologie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale qui s'y rattachent |trans-title=Notes on the classification of the carnivores, especially the Felidae, and the respective zoological studies |journal=Revue et Magasin de Zoologie Pure et Appliqu\u00e9e |volume=X |language=French| pages=385\u2013396 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revueetmagasinde10soci#page/390/mode/2up}}</ref> Later authors classified the jaguarundi in the genus ''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]'' along with the [[cougar]] (''P. concolor'').<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000211 |heading=Species ''Puma yagouaroundi'' |page=545}}</ref> In 2017, the [[IUCN]] Cat Specialist Group listed the jaguarundi as a [[monotypic taxon]] of the genus ''Herpailurus''.<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |display-authors=23 |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref> [[Phylogeography|Phylogeographical]] analysis of jaguarundi samples from across its range found no genetic evidence for [[subspecies]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |author2=Pinedo-Castro, M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |pages=245\u2013288 |chapter=Population genetics and phylogeographic analyses of the jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') by means of three mitochondrial markers: The first molecular study of this species |title=Molecular Population Genetics, Evolutionary Biology and Biological Conservation on Neotropical Carnivores |editor1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |editor2=Shostell, J. M. |publisher=Nova Publishers |location=New York |isbn=978-1-62417-079-9 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/230597248_Population_genetics_and_phylogeographic_of_the_jaguarundi_Puma_yaguaroundi_by_means_of_three_mitochondrial_markers_the_first_molecular_population_study_of_this_species_Chapter_8_Molecular_Population_G}}</ref>\n\n==Phylogeny and evolution==\n{{cladogram|title=\n|align=left\n|caption=The ''Puma'' lineage of the family [[Felidae]], depicted along with closely related genera.<ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W.E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae) |year=2010 |pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142 |editor1-last=Macdonald |editor1-first=D.W. |editor2-last=Loveridge |editor2-first=A.J. |title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-19-923445-5 |edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n|1={{clade | style=font-size:90%;line-height:100%;width:450px;\n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |label1=''Lynx'' lineage\n         |1=''[[Lynx (genus)|Lynx]]''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{clade\n            |label1=''Puma'' lineage\n            |1={{clade\n               |label1=''[[Acinonyx]]''\n               |1= ''Acinonyx jubatus'' <br/>([[Cheetah]]) |image1=[[File:Cynailurus guttata - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam - (white background).jpg|80px|left]]\n               |2={{clade\n                  |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n                  |1=''Puma concolor'' <br/>([[Cougar]]) |image1=[[File:Felis concolor - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam -(white background).jpg|70px|left]]\n                  |label2='''''Herpailurus'''''&nbsp;\n                  |2=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' <br/>('''Jaguarundi''')\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=Domestic cat lineage\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''\n            |label2=Leopard cat lineage\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Otocolobus]]''\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n}}\n\nThe jaguarundi is most closely related to the cougar and [[cheetah]].<ref name=\"Culver\">{{cite journal |author1=Culver, M. |author2=Johnson, W. E. |author3=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author4=O'Brien, S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2000 |title=Genomic Ancestry of the American Puma |journal=[[Journal of Heredity]] |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186 |pmid=10833043 |url-status=dead |url=http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616200443/http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> These three species together form the ''Puma'' lineage, one of the eight lineages of Felidae; the ''Puma'' lineage [[Genetic divergence|diverged]] from the rest 6.7 [[Mya (unit)|mya]]. The [[sister group]] of the ''Puma'' lineage is a [[clade]] of smaller [[Old World]] cats that includes the genera ''[[Felis]]'', ''[[Otocolobus]]'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]''.<ref name=\"werdelin\"/> \n\nThe three species of the ''Puma'' lineage may have had a [[common ancestor]] during the [[Miocene]], about {{mya|8.25}}.<ref name=\"adams\">{{cite journal |last1=Adams |first1=D. B. |title=The cheetah: native American |journal=Science |year=1979 |volume=205 |issue=4411 |pages=1155\u20131158 |doi=10.1126/science.205.4411.1155 |pmid=17735054 |bibcode=1979Sci...205.1155A |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6901/86b75e66b681ff0d83772f74068cd1b908b5.pdf}}</ref><ref name=johnson>{{cite journal |pmid=9071018 |year=1997 |last1=Johnson |first1=W. E. |last2=O'Brien |first2=S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Phylogenetic reconstruction of the Felidae using 16S rRNA and NADH-5 mitochondrial genes |volume=44 |issue=S1 |pages=S98\u2013S116 |journal=Journal of Molecular Evolution |doi=10.1007/PL00000060|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232587 |bibcode=1997JMolE..44S..98J}}</ref> ''Acinonyx'' possibly diverged from the lineage in the Americas;<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal |last1=Johnson |first1=W.E. |last2=Eizirik |first2=E. |last3=Pecon-Slattery |first3=J. |last4=Murphy |first4=W.J. |last5=Antunes |first5=A. |last6=Teeling |first6=E. |last7=O'Brien |first7=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |doi=10.1126/science.1122277 |title=The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=311 |pages=73\u201377 |pmid=16400146 |issue=5757 |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1230866}}</ref><ref name=dobrynin>{{cite journal |last1=Dobrynin |first1=P. |last2=Liu |first2=S. |last3=Tamazian |first3 = G. |last4=Xiong |first4=Z. |last5=Yurchenko |first5=A. A. |last6=Krasheninnikova |first6=K. |last7=Kliver |first7=S. |last8=Schmidt-K\u00fcntzel |first8=A. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genomic legacy of the African cheetah, ''Acinonyx jubatus'' |journal=Genome Biology |year=2015 |volume=16 |pages=277 |doi=10.1186/s13059-015-0837-4 |pmid=26653294 |pmc=4676127}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Brien |first1=S. J. |last2=Johnson |first2=W. E. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The evolution of cats |journal=Scientific American |date=2007 |volume=297 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201375 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0707-68 |url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/O%27brien2007EvolutionCats.pdf}}</ref> some authors alternatively suggest that the cheetah diverged in the Old World.<ref>{{cite journal |first=R. |last=Barnett |author2=I. B. |author3=Phillips, M. J. |author4=Martin, L. D. |author5=Harington, C. R. |author6=Leonard, J. A. |author7=Cooper, A. |year=2005 |title=Evolution of the extinct Sabretooths and the American cheetah-like cat |journal=[[Current Biology]] |volume=15 |issue=15 |pages=R589\u2013R590 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2005.07.052 |pmid=16085477}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faurby |first1=S. |last2=Werdelin |first2=L. |last3=Svenning |first3=J. C. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The difference between trivial and scientific names: there were never any true cheetahs in North America |journal=Genome Biology |year=2016 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=89 |doi=10.1186/s13059-016-0943-y|pmid=27150269 |pmc=4858926}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Puma'' lineage appears to have migrated from Asia to North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]], arriving in South America via the [[Isthmus of Panama]] by [[Late Pliocene]] or [[Early Pleistocene]]. This was possibly followed by the bifurcation of the lineage into the cougar and ''Herpailurus'' (represented by ''H. pumoides'') in South America around {{mya|4|3}} between the Late Pliocene and Early Pleistocene. ''H. pumoides'' went extinct around [[Middle Pleistocene]], around the time the modern jaguarundi came into existence; the oldest fossils of the modern jaguarundi date back to the [[Late Pleistocene]] in Brazil around {{mya|0.5}}. The original North American cougars were extripated during the [[Pleistocene extinctions]] around 10,000 years ago; then North America was recolonized by South American cougars and jaguarundis 10,000\u20138,000 years ago.<ref name=bellani/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Culver |first1=M. |title=Genomic ancestry of the American puma (''Puma concolor'') |journal=Journal of Heredity |date=2000 |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chimento |first1=N.R. |last2=Dondas |first2=A. |title=First record of ''Puma concolor'' (Mammalia, Felidae) in the Early-Middle Pleistocene of South America |journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution |date=2017 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=381\u2013389 |doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9385-x}}</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header    = \n| header_align = center\n\n| image1    = Jaguarondi 2.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = <center>Red morph</center>\n\n| image2    = Jaguarundi seitlich.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  = <center>Gray morph</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}} \nThe jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats in its external appearance. This has been attributed to variations in its [[karyotype]]\u2014the jaguarundi has 38 [[chromosome]]s, unlike the 36 in other small South American cats, and the chromosomal features resemble those of Old World cats such as the [[leopard cat]] (''Prionailurus bengalensis'').<ref name=WCoW/> Interestingly, the jaguarundi is characterized by several [[mustelid]] features\u2014an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. As such, the jaguarundi is sometimes considered similar to [[marten]]s, [[otter]]s or [[weasel]]s.<ref name=\"bellani\">{{cite book |last1=Bellani |first1=G.G. |title=Felines of the World: Discoveries in Taxonomic Classification and History |date=2020 |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-12-816503-4 |pages=223-231 |url={{Google Books|id=xK2wDwAAQBAJ|page=223|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|page=818|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=818|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The head-and-body length is between {{convert|53|and|77|cm|in|abbr=on}}; the strong, muscular tail is {{convert|31|\u2013|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though larger individuals weighing around {{convert|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}} have been reported.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |author1=Sunquist, M. |author2=Sunquist, F. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild Cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |pages=113\u2013119 |isbn= 978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/113}}</ref><ref name=\"fws.gov\">{{Cite journal |author1=Brown, D.E. |author2=Gonzalez, C.A. |year=1999 |title=Jaguarundi (''Felis yagouaroundi tolteca'') |url=http://www.fws.gov/southwest/es/Arizona/Documents/Redbook/Jaguarundi%20RB.pdf |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |issue=32 |pages=155\u2013157}}</ref> Males are slightly larger than females.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nThe coat is uniformly colored with at most a few faint markings on the face and the belly, though kittens may be spotted for a short duration. Black and white marks on the lips and the snout, similar to those of the cougar, can be clearly seen in juveniles and some adults. The fur color varies from blackish to brownish-grey with a grizzled look due to alternating bright and dark rings on individual hairs (called gray [[Morph (biology)|morph]]), to foxy red to chestnut (called red morph); earlier these morphs were considered two different species. Individuals of both colors can be born in the same litter.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=\"hildyard\">{{cite book |last1=Sirimarco |first1=E. |editor1-last=Hildyard |editor1-first=A. |title=Endangered Wildlife and Plants of the World (Volume 6) |date=2001 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Co |location=New York |isbn=0-7614-7200-2 |pages=736-738 |chapterurl={{Google Books|plainurl=yes|id=5YYqd4ROFfkC|page=736}} |chapter=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yaguarondi cacomitli'')}}</ref> Blackish brown individuals superficially resemble the [[tayra]] (''Eira barbara''), but the latter can be told apart by the clear, yellowish patch on the throat.<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite journal |last1=de Oliveira |first1=T.G. |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |journal=Mammalian Species |date=1998 |issue=578 |pages=1-6 |doi=10.2307/3504500 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275737351_Herpailurus_yagouaroundi}}</ref> The red morph is seen more often in dry, open areas. [[Melanism|melanistic]] individuals have been reported, but they are not completely black; the head and the throat are clearly paler than the rest of the body.<ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=152\u2013156|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=152|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref>  The ears, {{convert|2.5|\u2013|4|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, are widely spaced and, unlike many other felids, lack white spots on the back.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos>{{cite book |author1-last=Aranda |author1-first=M. |author2-last=Caso |author2-first=A. |editor1-last=Ceballos |editor1-first=G. |title=Mammals of Mexico |publisher=John Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-1-4214-0879-8 |pages=498-499 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl={{Google Books|page=498|plainurl=yes|id=UrvxBQAAQBAJ}}}}</ref> The jaguarundi has a total of 30 teeth; the [[dental formula]] is {{DentalFormula|upper=3.1.3.1|lower=3.1.2.1}}.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nAmong felids, the jaguarundi is closely similar to the [[flat-headed cat]] (''Prionailurus planiceps''), but has a longer body and proportionately longer legs, is heavier and lacks the dark markings on the cheeks of the flat-headed cat.<ref name=ms/> Tawny jaguarundis bear a similar coloration as the signficantly larger cougar.<ref name=Hunter/>\n\n==Behavior and ecology==\n[[File:Jaguarondi 1.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are good climbers and can easily walk on branches.]]\nThe jaguarundi is shy and reclusive, and apparently very cautious of [[Animal trapping|traps]].<ref name=Simberloff/> There have been only a few [[radio telemetry]] studies of jaguarundis in Belize, Brazil and Mexico.<ref name=Hunter/> Though activity has been observed throughout the day and at night, jaguarundis seem to prefer hunting during daytime and evening hours; a study in Belize reported that jaguarundis started moving before dawn and remained active through most of the day till sunset with a peak in hunting from late morning to noon.<ref name=ms/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Konecny |first1=M.J. |title=Movement patterns and food habits of four sympatric carnivore species in Belize, South America |journal=Advances in Neotropical Mammalogy |date=1989 |pages=243-264 |url=http://library.bfreebz.org/Mammals/Michael%20Konecny,%20Movement%20Patterns%20and%20Food%20Habits%20of%20Four%20Sympatric%20Carnivore%20Species%20in%20Belize,%20Central%20America,%201989.pdf}}</ref> The cat appears to be more [[Diurnality|diurnal]] than most other cats, especially spotted cats that tend to be more active at night.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=WCoW/> The jaguarundi can swim across medium-sized rivers; an individual was recorded swimming across the [[Tuichi River]] (Bolivia).<ref name=Hunter/> Jaguarundis are efficient climbers as well, but hunt mainly on ground; its coat color works as a good camouflage for terrestrial activity.<ref name=Nowak/> They can leap up to {{convert|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} into the air to catch birds.<ref name=WCoW/> Predators recorded for jaguarundis include [[boa constrictor]]s, cougars and [[domestic dog]]s.<ref name=Hunter/> Parasites such as [[hookworm]]s (''[[Ancylostoma]]'' species), [[tapeworm]]s (such as  ''[[Spirometra]]'' and ''[[Toxocara]]'' species) and the [[lung fluke]] have been found in jaguarundis.<ref name=ms/>\n\nStudies have mostly observed jaguarundis alone or in pairs; pairs could probably be formed between mothers and older kittens or between individuals of opposite sexes during the mating season. Individuals in captivity have been found to be more gregarious.<ref name=WCoW/> [[Home range]]s tend to be large; a study in Brazil recorded home ranges {{convert|1.4|\u2013|18|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size for females, while those of males measured {{convert|8.5|\u2013|25.3|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in area.<ref name=Hunter/> Two males in Belize were recorded to have exceptionally large home ranges spanning an area of {{convert|88|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} and {{convert|100|sqkm|sqmi}}, while the home range of a female in the same region measured {{convert|13|\u2013|20|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size.<ref name=Nowak/> Population densities are typically low, around {{convert|0.01|to|0.05|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}, though the Llanos in Costa Rica and Venezuela have recorded figures as high as {{convert|0.2|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=bellani/>\n\nMarking behavior could serve as a means of olfactory or visual communication; individuals in captivity have been observed scraping areas with their hind feet (sometimes with urination), clawing on logs, rubbing objects with their heads and leaving feces uncovered. Social behavior such as grooming, growling and sniffing has been recorded. The jaguarundi has a broad vocal repertoire; 13 different calls have been recorded including chattering, purring, screaming, a 'wah-wah' call, whistling, yapping and a peculiar bird-like chirp. In captivity, females in [[estrus]] have been observed making faint sounds as they [[scent mark]] the area around their enclosures.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/> \n\n===Diet===\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi, ZOO Praha 254.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are [[Generalist and specialist species|generalist]] carnivores.]]\nThe jaguarundi typically feed on small-sized prey weighing less than {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, including ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Jaguarundis will also take larger prey such as domestic poultry, fish, [[marmoset]]s, rabbits and [[opossum]]s; a study recorded small deer (possibly [[carrion]]) in the diet. Vegetation such as grasses have also been recorded in their diet.<ref name=Hunter/><ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/><ref name=ms/> A study showed jaguarundis take {{convert|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} vertebrate prey on an average everyday.<ref name=ms/> The broad array of prey recorded for the jaguarundi across its range and varying proportions of different prey in its diet could indicate that the cat tends to feed on the most abundant and easily catchable prey in the area.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nJaguarundis have been observed mating all year round, with peaks at different times of the year across the range; for instance, in Mexico breeding peaks in January and March. Estrus lasts three to five days, marked by the female regularly rolling onto her back and [[spraying urine]]. [[Sexually mature]] males will pursue the female, not reacting to any aggressive behavior from her side. As in many other felids, the male bites the fur on the female's neck on mounting; the female lets out a loud scream on penetration.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/>\n\nAfter a [[gestation]] period of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens in a den constructed in a dense thicket, hollow tree, or similar cover. The kittens are covered well with fur and the underside is marked with spots, which disappear as they age; the coat color gradually changes as the kittens grow older.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/> The mother starts bringing solid food for the kittens when they are around three weeks old, who simply play with it till the mother ingests it; kittens are capable of taking solid food like birds and guinea pigs at around six weeks. Jaguarundis become sexually mature at one to three years of age. Lifespan up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=Nowak/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe jaguarundi inhabits a wide variety of habitats\u2014from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. It can also occur in [[cloud forest]]s, [[mangrove]]s and [[savanna]]s.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=ceballos/> Unlike the [[Sympatry|sympatric]] [[margay]], [[ocelot]] and [[oncilla]], the jaguarundi can occur in open areas as well. In open habitats the jaguarundi prefers areas with vegetative cover such as cacti, which would generally be difficult for possible predators to penetrate; there may be a few clearings at the periphery of such areas. Jaguarundis tend to stay close to a source of running water.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=fws.gov/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Coronado-Quibrera |first1=W.P. |last2=Olmos-Oropeza |first2=G. |last3=Bender |first3=L.C. |last4=Rosas-Rosas |first4=O.C. |last5=Palacio-N\u00fa\u00f1ez |first5=J. |last6=Tarango-Ar\u00e1mbula |first6=L.A. |last7=Herrera-Haro |first7=J.G. |title=Adaptability of the threatened jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Schereber, 1777) to human-altered environments in San Luis Potos\u00ed, Mexico |journal=Acta Zool\u00f3gica Mexicana |date=2019 |volume=35 |pages=1\u201315 |doi=10.21829/azm.2019.3502210 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/310f/6597fd914eb664e160637b4b1b1d57d87fe7.pdf}}</ref> The jaguarundi is noted for its resistance to environmental disturbances in its habitat; it can successfully thrive in reforested areas.<ref name=ceballos/> While commonly inhabiting lowlands up to {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the sea level, this cat has been reported at elevations as high as {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Colombia.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThe range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the Andes\u2014second only to the cougar in the [[Latitude|latitudinal]] extent of its distribution. However, not all parts of its range have been studied well. The jaguarundi is fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela.<ref name=\"rev\">{{cite journal |last1=Giordano |first1=A.J. |title=Ecology and status of the jaguarundi ''Puma yagouaroundi'': a synthesis of existing knowledge |journal=Mammal Review |date=2016 |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201343 |doi=10.1111/mam.12051 |url=https://carnivores.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Giordano_2015_mam12051_Jaguarundi.pdf}}</ref> It is possibly [[extinct]] in the US;<ref name=iucn/> a study in 1999 refuted claims of sightings in Arizona.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=D.E. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez |first2=C.A.L. |title=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Geoffroy 1803) not in Arizona or Sonora |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |date=1999 |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=155-157 |jstor=40021308}}</ref> The last confirmed sighting in the US was probably of a roadkilled individual near [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] (Texas) in 1986.<ref name=rev/>\n\nJaguarundis have been sighted in [[Florida]] since the early 20th century; their presence there is attributed to a writer from [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]] who at some point imported the animals from their native habitat and released them near his hometown and in other locations across the state. Several sightings have been reported since 1907; in 1977 [[W. T. Neill]] noted that the population was declining. Jaguarundis have also been reported in the coastal area of [[Alabama]] since the 1980s, which may be evidence of the Florida population migrating northward.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title=Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida |last1=Simberloff |first1=D. |authorlink=Daniel Simberloff |author2=Schmitz, D.C. |author3=Brown, T.C. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1997 |publisher=Island Press |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-55963-430-4 |url={{Google Books |plainurl=yes|page=172|id=rtrpSllq4SQC}} |pages=172\u2013173}}</ref> The jaguarundi has also been recorded from [[Cerro Largo Department|Cerro Largo]] in [[Uruguay]], where its presence was doubted.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Grattarola, F. |author2=Hernandez, D. |author3=Duarte, A. |author4=Gaucher, L. |author5=Perazza, G. |display-authors=3 |year=2016 |title=Primer registro de yaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) en Uruguay, con comentarios sobre monitereo participativo |journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Zool\u00f3gica del Uruguay |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=85\u221291 |language=Spanish |trans-title=First record of jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) in Uruguay, with comments on participatory monitoring}}</ref>\n\n==Threats and conservation==\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi.jpg|thumb|left|Captive jaguarundi in the Zoo de Pont-Scorff (France)]]\nThe jaguarundi has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2002. Mexican populations, except those in the northeast, appear to be stable. The huge reserves of the [[Amazon Basin]] are probably the only conservation units that can sustain long-term viable populations. In its 2015 revision, the IUCN noted that the species should be listed as [[Near Threatened]], but there was not enough data to go upon to extend this classification throughout the range.<ref name=iucn/> The jaguarundi is not particularly sought after for its fur due to its poor quality and low value, but is suffering decline due to habitat loss.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=fws.gov/> Other threats include risks of [[habitat fragmentation]] and persecution for killing poultry.<ref name=iucn/> The North and Central American populations of the jaguarundi are listed in [[CITES Appendix I]] and all the other populations are listed in [[CITES Appendix II]].<ref name=ceballos/> Populations in the US are protected under the [[Endangered Species Act]];<ref name=MSW3/> the [[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]] has expressed concern that its presence in South Texas may be imperiled due to loss of the cat's native habitat.<ref name=Texas2003>{{cite web |url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/landwater/land/habitats/southtx_plain/endangered_species/ |title=Endangered Species |website=Tpwd.state.tx.us |date=2003-04-15 |access-date=2011-09-15 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Populations in Mexico are listed under the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lorenzo |first1=C. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez-Ruiz |first2=N. |title=Mammals in the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010 |journal=Therya |date=2018 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=69\u201372 |doi=10.12933/therya-18-565 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323250093_Mammals_in_the_Mexican_Official_Norm_NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010}}</ref> Hunting jaguarundi is restricted in Peru and banned in Argentina, Belize, Brazil, Bolivia, Colombia, Costa Rica, French Guiana, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Panama, Paraguay, Suriname, Uruguay, the US and Venezuela.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Acinonychini]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons and category|Puma yagouaroundi|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=93 |title=Jaguarundi ''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |website=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group}}\n* {{cite web |website=Big Cats Online |url=http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031107150747/http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-date=2003-11-07 |df=dmy-all |title=Jaguarundi |series=Wild Cat Species and Distribution \u2013 South America}}\n* {{cite Americana |wstitle=Jaguarondi |short=x}}\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q182304}}\n\n[[Category:Puma (genus)]]\n[[Category:Felids of Central America]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Felids of South America]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Belize]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of French Guiana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Honduras]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Suriname]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Panama]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Peru]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Fauna of northern South America]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1803]]\n[[Category:Guaran\u00ed words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Sainsf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePhylogeny and evolution:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaguarundi"}
{"title_page": "Wayne Pratt", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Wayne Pratt\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1960|3|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Southampton]], England\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}<ref name=\"ATS435\"/>\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = Price's College\n| youthyears2    = 1976\u20131978\n| youthclubs2    = [[Southampton F.C. Academy|Southampton]]\n| years1         = 1978\u20131981\n| clubs1         = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n| caps1          = 1\n| goals1         = 0\n| years2         = 1981\u20131982\n| clubs2         = [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]]\n| caps2          = \n| goals2         = \n| years3         = 1982\n| clubs3         = Mein Munkfors\n| caps3          = \n| goals3         = \n| years4         = 1982\u20131984\n| clubs4         = [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]]\n| caps4          = \n| goals4         = \n| years5         = 1984\u20131985\n| clubs5         = [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]]\n| caps5          = \n| goals5         = \n| years6         = 1985\u20131987\n| clubs6         = [[Andover F.C.|Andover]]\n| caps6          = \n| goals6         = \n| years7         = 1987\n| clubs7         = [[Road-Sea Southampton F.C.|Road-Sea Southampton]]\n| caps7          = \n| goals7         = \n}}\n'''Wayne Pratt''' (born 1 March 1960)<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> is an English retired professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]]. Born in [[Southampton]], Pratt began his career with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 1978, and later played for local clubs including [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]] and [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]].\n\n==Career==\nWayne Pratt initially joined the [[Southampton F.C. Academy]] as an apprentice in July 1976 at the age of 16, before signing professional terms in March 1978.<ref name=\"ATS435\">{{harvnb|Chalk|Holley|Bull|2013|p=435}}</ref> He made his first and only appearance for the club on 22 November 1980 in a [[Football League First Division]] match against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], as a replacement for the injured [[Steve Williams (footballer, born 1958)|Steve Williams]].<ref name=\"ITN159\">{{harvnb|Holley|Chalk|Bull|2003|p=159}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Southampton v Leeds United, 22 November 1980|url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/southampton-v-leeds-united-22-november-1980-85528/|publisher=11v11.com|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> He did not return the following week, when he himself was replaced by the debuting [[Reuben Agboola]].<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> During the [[1980\u201381 in English football|1980\u201381 season]] Pratt also captained the Southampton Reserves,<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> playing in 31 of the side's games in the [[The Football Combination|Football Combination]] that year and scoring one goal, against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref name=\"ITN456\">{{harvnb|Holley|Chalk|Bull|2003|p=456}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Southampton in 1981, Pratt played for a number of clubs in [[Hampshire]], including two spells at [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]], a season with [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]] and two years at [[Andover F.C.|Andover]].<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> In 1982, he also briefly played for Swedish club Mein Munkfors, as well as having a trial at [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in October.<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> In 1987 the midfielder played for [[Road-Sea Southampton F.C.|Road-Sea Southampton]] in their final season before dissolution, and he later spent time at [[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]], [[Poole Town F.C.|Poole Town]] and Netley Central Sports.<ref name=\"ITN567\">{{harvnb|Holley|Chalk|Bull|2003|p=567}}</ref> As of 2013 Pratt was the director of Southampton & District Tyro League side Sarisbury Sparks, as well as working in the building trade in the [[Locks Heath]] area.<ref name=\"ATS435\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography ==\n*{{Citation |last=Chalk |first=Gary |last2=Holley |first2=Duncan |last3=Bull |first3=David |date=2013 |title=All the Saints: A Complete Players' Who's Who of Southampton FC |publisher=Hagiology Publishing |isbn=978-0992686406 }}\n*{{Citation |last=Holley |first=Duncan |last2=Chalk |first2=Gary |last3=Bull |first3=David |date=2003 |title=In That Number: A Post-War Chronicle of Southampton FC |publisher=Hagiology Publishing |isbn=978-0953447435 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pratt, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Waterlooville F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gosport Borough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Andover F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Road-Sea Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Weymouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Poole Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Southampton]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Wayne Pratt\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1960|3|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Southampton]], England\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}<ref name=\"ATS435\"/>\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = Price's College\n| youthyears2    = 1976\u20131978\n| youthclubs2    = [[Southampton F.C. Academy|Southampton]]\n| years1         = 1978\u20131981\n| clubs1         = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n| caps1          = 1\n| goals1         = 0\n| years2         = 1981\u20131982\n| clubs2         = [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]]\n| caps2          = \n| goals2         = \n| years3         = 1982\n| clubs3         = Mein Munkfors\n| caps3          = \n| goals3         = \n| years4         = 1982\u20131984\n| clubs4         = [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]]\n| caps4          = \n| goals4         = \n| years5         = 1984\u20131985\n| clubs5         = [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]]\n| caps5          = \n| goals5         = \n| years6         = 1985\u20131987\n| clubs6         = [[Andover F.C.|Andover]]\n| caps6          = \n| goals6         = \n| years7         = 1987\n| clubs7         = [[Road-Sea Southampton F.C.|Road-Sea Southampton]]\n| caps7          = \n| goals7         = \n}}\n'''Wayne Pratt''' (born 1 March 1960)<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> is a retired English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]]. Born in [[Southampton]], Pratt began his career with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 1978, and later played for local clubs including [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]] and [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]].\n\n==Career==\nWayne Pratt initially joined the [[Southampton F.C. Academy]] as an apprentice in July 1976 at the age of 16, before signing professional terms in March 1978.<ref name=\"ATS435\">{{harvnb|Chalk|Holley|Bull|2013|p=435}}</ref> He made his first and only appearance for the club on 22 November 1980 in a [[Football League First Division]] match against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], as a replacement for the injured [[Steve Williams (footballer, born 1958)|Steve Williams]].<ref name=\"ITN159\">{{harvnb|Holley|Chalk|Bull|2003|p=159}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Southampton v Leeds United, 22 November 1980|url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/southampton-v-leeds-united-22-november-1980-85528/|publisher=11v11.com|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> He did not return the following week, when he himself was replaced by the debuting [[Reuben Agboola]].<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> During the [[1980\u201381 in English football|1980\u201381 season]] Pratt also captained the Southampton Reserves,<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> playing in 31 of the side's games in the [[The Football Combination|Football Combination]] that year and scoring one goal, against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref name=\"ITN456\">{{harvnb|Holley|Chalk|Bull|2003|p=456}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Southampton in 1981, Pratt played for a number of clubs in [[Hampshire]], including two spells at [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]], a season with [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]] and two years at [[Andover F.C.|Andover]].<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> In 1982, he also briefly played for Swedish club Mein Munkfors, as well as having a trial at [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in October.<ref name=\"ATS435\"/> In 1987 the midfielder played for [[Road-Sea Southampton F.C.|Road-Sea Southampton]] in their final season before dissolution, and he later spent time at [[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]], [[Poole Town F.C.|Poole Town]] and Netley Central Sports.<ref name=\"ITN567\">{{harvnb|Holley|Chalk|Bull|2003|p=567}}</ref> As of 2013 Pratt was the director of Southampton & District Tyro League side Sarisbury Sparks, as well as working in the building trade in the [[Locks Heath]] area.<ref name=\"ATS435\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography ==\n*{{Citation |last=Chalk |first=Gary |last2=Holley |first2=Duncan |last3=Bull |first3=David |date=2013 |title=All the Saints: A Complete Players' Who's Who of Southampton FC |publisher=Hagiology Publishing |isbn=978-0992686406 }}\n*{{Citation |last=Holley |first=Duncan |last2=Chalk |first2=Gary |last3=Bull |first3=David |date=2003 |title=In That Number: A Post-War Chronicle of Southampton FC |publisher=Hagiology Publishing |isbn=978-0953447435 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pratt, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Waterlooville F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gosport Borough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Andover F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Road-Sea Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Weymouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Poole Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Southampton]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayne_Pratt"}
{"title_page": "I Dare You (Kelly Clarkson song)", "text_new": "{{under construction}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = I Dare You\n| cover         = Kelly Clarkson - I Dare You single cover.png\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Kelly Clarkson]]\n| language      = {{Flatlist}}\n* Arabic\n* English\n* French\n* German\n* Hebrew\n* Spanish\n{{Endflatlist}}\n| released      = {{Start date|2020|04|16}}\n| format        = \n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded      = 2019\n| genre         = \n| length        = {{Duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label         = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer        =\n* [[Jesse Shatkin]]\n* [[Jeff Gitelman]]\n* [[Natalie Hemby]]\n* Laura Veltz\n* [[Ben West (musician)|Ben West]]\n| producer      = Jesse Shatkin\n| prev_title    = [[Broken & Beautiful (song)|Broken & Beautiful]]\n| prev_year     = 2019\n| next_title    =\n| next_year     = \n}}\n\n\"'''I Dare You'''\" is a song by American singer [[Kelly Clarkson]]. Produced and written by [[Jesse Shatkin]], with additional writing by [[Natalie Hemby]], Laura Veltz, [[Ben West (musician)|Ben West]], and [[Jeff Gitelman|Jeff \"Gitty\" Gitelman]], it was released as a stand-alone single by [[Atlantic Records]] on April 16, 2020. Unlike her previous records, its single release includes multiple versions of the song recorded in several languages as a [[duet]] featuring various recording artists \u2014 such as French singer [[Zaz (singer)|Zaz]], Canadian-Moroccan singer [[Faouzia]] for the Arabic version, Spanish singer [[Blas Cant\u00f3]], German musical duo [[Glasperlenspiel (duo)|Glasperlenspiel]], Israeli singer [[Maya Bouskilla]] for the Hebrew version, and the American [[Deaf West Theatre]] for the [[ASL]] version.\n\n== Composition and release ==\n\"I Dare You\" was written by [[Jesse Shatkin]] and [[Jeff Gitelman|Gitty]], [[Natalie Hemby]], Laura Veltz and [[Ben West (musician)|Ben West]].<ref>{{cite web |title=I Dare You to Love (Kelly Clarkson ver.) |url=https://www.warnerchappell.com/song-details/WW%20015349870%2000/dd46778e-a982-4232-c639-f16cd3a71ec6 |publisher=[[Warner Chappell Music]] |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In her opening monologue on a February 2020 episode of her [[The Kelly Clarkson Show|self-titled talk show]], Clarkson revealed her plans to release the song.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wass |first1=Mike |title=Kelly Clarkson Is Releasing A New Single Called \"I Dare You\" |url=https://www.idolator.com/7907322/kelly-clarkson-is-releasing-a-new-single-called-i-dare-you |website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |publisher=Hive Media |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Israeli singer [[Maya Bouskilla]] also announced that she was invited by [[Warner Music Group]] ([[Atlantic Records]]'s parent label) to record the song as a duet with Clarkson as part of a single release featuring select recording artists from all over the world,<ref name=\"Walla\">{{cite web |title=\u05e8\u05e9\u05de\u05d9\u05ea: \u05e7\u05dc\u05d9 \u05e7\u05dc\u05e8\u05e7\u05e1\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e7\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d4 \u05d3\u05d5\u05d0\u05d8 \u05e2\u05dd \u05de\u05d0\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d5\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9\u05dc\u05d4 \u05d1\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea |trans-title=Official: Kelly Clarkson recorded a duet with Maya Buskilla in Hebrew |language=Hebrew |url=https://e.walla.co.il/item/3346123 |first=Sagi |last=Ben-Nun |publisher=[[Walla!]] |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> which included French singer [[Zaz (singer)|Zaz]], Canadian-Moroccan singer [[Faouzia]], Spanish singer [[Blas Cant\u00f3]], and German musical duo [[Glasperlenspiel (duo)|Glasperlenspiel]]. She also announced plans to film the single's debut live performance on ''[[The Kelly Clarkson Show]]'' on March 24, its original intended date of release, but was halted due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Walla\" /> On April 3, 2020, Clarkson formally announced the single, which is set to be released on April 16, 2020, accompanied by a special episode of ''The Kelly Clarkson Show'' the same day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kubota |first1=Samantha |title=Kelly Clarkson reveals new music coming later this month |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/kelly-clarkson-reveals-new-music-coming-later-month-t177505 |website=[[Today (American TV program)|The Today Show]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> A 30-seconds snippet of the song has been posted on Clarkson's social media on April 14, 2020.\n\n== Track listing ==\n;Single \u2013 Multi-language Duets<ref name=\"Release - Multi-language Duets\">{{cite web |title=I Dare You (Multi-Language Duets) |url=https://open.spotify.com/album/4OUdmzLsYYpcUbCPS7TTZ7 |publisher=[[Spotify]] |date=April 16, 2020 |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| title1  = I Dare You\n| writer1 = \n{{Flatlist|\n* [[Jesse Shatkin]]\n* [[Jeff Gitelman]]\n* [[Natalie Hemby]]\n* Laura Veltz\n* [[Ben West (musician)|Ben West]]\n}}\n| length1 = 3:36\n\n| title2  = I Dare You (Appelle ton amour)\n| note2   = featuring [[Zaz (singer)|Zaz]]\n| writer2 = \n{{Flatlist|\n* [[:fr:Doriand|Doriand]]\n* [[Zaz (singer)|Isabelle Geffroy]]\n}}\n| length2 = 3:38\n\n| title3  = I Dare You (\u0643\u0646\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0627\u0643)\n| note3   = featuring [[Faouzia]]\n| writer3 = [[Faouzia|Faouzia Ouihya]]\n| length3 = 3:36\n\n| title4  = I Dare You (Te Reto A Amar)\n| note4   = featuring [[Blas Cant\u00f3]]\n| writer4 = \n{{Flatlist|\n* Blas Cant\u00f3\n* Daniel Ortega\n* Emilio Mercader\n* Daniel Hammond Pascual\n}}\n| length4 = 3:36\n\n| title5  = I Dare You (Trau Dich)\n| note5   = featuring [[Glasperlenspiel (duo)|Glasperlenspiel]]\n| writer5 =\n{{Flatlist|\n* Max Embers\n* Carolin Niemczyk\n}}\n| length5 = 3:36\n\n| title6  = I Dare You (\u05d1\u05d5\u05d0 \u05e0\u05e8\u05d0\u05d4)\n| note6   = featuring [[Maya Bouskilla]]\n| writer6 = Noam Horev\n| length6 = 3:36\n}}\n\n== Pe