{"title_page": "Wayne O'Sullivan", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| image = \n| name = Wayne O'Sullivan\n| fullname = Wayne St John O'Sullivan\n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|2|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Akrotiri and Dhekelia|Akrotiri]], [[Cyprus]]\n| position = [[Midfielder|Right midfield]]\n| youthyears1 = pre\u20131994\n| youthclubs1 = [[Swindon Town]]\n| years1 = 1994\u20131997\n| years2 = 1997\u20131999\n| years3 = 1999\u20132001\n| years4 = 2001\u20132003\n| years5 = 2003\u20132004\n| years6 = 2004\n| years7 = 2005\u20132007\n| years8 = 2011\n| clubs1 = [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n| clubs2 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| clubs3 = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n| clubs4 = [[Parramatta Power]]\n| clubs5 = [[Northern Spirit FC|Northern Spirit]]\n| clubs6 = [[Geylang United]]\n| clubs7 = [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]]\n| clubs8 = [[Lake Macquarie City FC|Lake Macquarie City]]\n| caps1 = 89\n| goals1 = 3\n| caps2 = 85\n| goals2 = 4\n| caps3 = 85\n| goals3 = 3\n| caps4 = 55\n| goals4 = 2\n| caps5 = 24\n| goals5 = 0\n| caps6 = \n| goals6 = 4\n| caps7 = 37\n| goals7 = 1\n| caps8 = 11\n| goals8 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1995\n| nationalteam1 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2004\n| managerclubs1 = [[Geylang United FC|Geylang United]]\n| manageryears2 = 2008\u20132009\n| managerclubs2 = [[Wellington Phoenix]] (asst.)\n| manageryears3 = 2009\u20132012\n| managerclubs3 = [[Newcastle Jets FC W-League]]\n| manageryears4 = 2013\u20132015\n| managerclubs4 = [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] (asst.)\n| manageryears5 = 2018\n| managerclubs5 = [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears6 = 2019 - current\n| managerclubs6 = [[Bonnyrigg White Eagles F.C.]]\n}}\n'''Wayne St John O'Sullivan''' (born February 25, 1974) is an Irish retired professional [[Association football|footballer]]. Since retiring as a player he has worked as a coach.\n\nBorn in Cyprus, O'Sullivan played youth football for [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] before making his professional debut with the club. In 2001, he moved to Australia, where he played in the [[National Soccer League]] and [[A-League]], as well as one season in Singapore.\n\nO'Sullivan represented [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland at youth level]].\n\nO'Sullivan is the current caretaker coach for [[A-League]] side [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\nO'Sullivan was part of the regular first eleven for [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]. At the time Plymouth were placed low in the [[Football League Third Division|Nationwide Division 3]] (now [[Football League Two]]), he along with [[Paul McGregor (footballer)|Paul McGregor]] and [[Martin Phillips (footballer)|Martin Phillips]] were considered the most consistent players at the time. But in the summer of 2000 he headed to Australia to continue his playing career.\n\nFollowing the demise of the old [[National Soccer League]] competition and the creation of the [[A-League]], O'Sullivan signed with [[Central Coast Mariners]] in late 2004 to play in the newly-formed A-League.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Soccer/Player-drain-as-Victory-delays/2004/12/14/1102787077306.html|title=Player drain as Victory delays|newspaper=[[The Age]]|date=15 December 2004|accessdate=14 April 2017|author=Lynch, Michael}}</ref> At the club, he was a favourite among fans for his tenacity and energy on the field. After an inconsistent 2006\u201307 season with The Mariners, during which he was often deployed as a right-back, instead of his preferred right-midfield position, the hard-working midfielder/defender was released.\n\nAlthough there is some controversy surrounding [[Lawrie McKinna]]'s decision to release O'Sullivan, it was believed by many in the Mariners camp that he was past his best and for the club to continue to grow in a developing league, his release was necessary.\n\n===International===\nO'Sullivan came on as a substitute for [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland under-21]] in a win over [[Latvia national under-21 football team|Latvia]] in [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] on 10 October 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/republic-of-ireland-v-latvia-10-october-1995-258874/|title=Republic of Ireland v Latvia, 10 October 1995|publisher=11v11.com|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref> He made a total of two appearances for the side.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindon-town-fc.co.uk/Person.asp?PersonID=OSULLIVW|title=Wayne O'Sullivan|publisher=[[Swindon Town F.C.]]|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nAfter being released by Central Coast Mariners, O'Sullivan had spent months trying to find a spot in another football team to continue his playing career, but was not successful.\n\nHe holds an Asian Federation Advance Level ([[FIFA]]) 'B' coaching licence and in July will graduate from Sydney University with a master's degree in education, specialising in coaching.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nOn Friday, 18 May 2007, O'Sullivan was named Assistant Coach for [[A-League]] club [[Wellington Phoenix]] on a two-year deal. He worked alongside [[Ricki Herbert]], [[Luciano Trani]] and former [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] goalkeeper [[Jonathan Gould]].\n\nOn Thursday, 21 November 2013, O'Sullivan was named Assistant Coach for the [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] on a contract until the end of the 2014\u201315 A-League season, working alongside newly appointed coach [[Phil Moss]].\n\nFollowing the immediate departure of Central Coast Mariner's Head Coach [[Paul Okon]], O'Sullivan was named as the caretaker coach until the end of the [[2017\u201318 A-League|2017\u201318 A-League season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/paul-okon-quits-as-mariners-boss-after-disappointing-a-league-campaign-20180320-p4z5b2.html|title=Paul Okon quits as Mariners boss after disappointing A-League campaign|first=Emma|last=Kemp|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn Thursday, 16 My 2019, O'Sullivan was appointed as new coach for the remainder of the 2019 [[National Premier Leagues NSW 2]] season with the [[Bonnyrigg White Eagles FC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://footballnsw.com.au/2019/05/16/wayne-osullivan-appointed-new-bonnyrigg-white-eagles-coach/|title=WAYNE O'SULLIVAN APPOINTED NEW BONNYRIGG WHITE EAGLES COACH|accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|6 May 2018}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|Nat\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]]\n|{{flagicon|Australia}}\n|align=left|20 March 2018\n|align=left|10 April 2018\n{{WDL|4|0|0|4}}\n|-\n!colspan=4|Total\n{{WDLtot|4|0|0|4}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;[[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n*[[Football League Second Division]]: [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393]]\n\n;[[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]]\n*[[A-League Pre-Season Challenge Cup]]: [[2005 A-League Pre-Season Challenge Cup|2005]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Plymouth Argyle F.C. Player of the Year]]: [[2000\u201301 Plymouth Argyle F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.swindon-town-fc.co.uk/Person.asp?PersonID=OSULLIVW Swindown Town FC]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110718025017/http://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/default.aspx?s=wellfc_news_item&id=17822 A-league Profile]\n* [http://www.cardiffcityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Welcome Cardiff City FC]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100801213543/http://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/default.aspx?s=aleague_team]\n* [http://www.lakemacquariecityfc.com]\n* [https://footballnsw.com.au/2019/05/16/wayne-osullivan-appointed-new-bonnyrigg-white-eagles-coach/]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Plymouth Argyle F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Central Coast Mariners FC head coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osullivan, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:National Soccer League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Central Coast Mariners FC players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northern Spirit FC players]]\n[[Category:Parramatta Power players]]\n[[Category:Plymouth Argyle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Geylang International FC players]]\n[[Category:Lake Macquarie City FC players]]\n[[Category:Central Coast Mariners FC non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Singapore Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Bonnyrigg White Eagles FC managers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland football managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| image = \n| name = Wayne O'Sullivan\n| fullname = Wayne St John O'Sullivan\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|2|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Akrotiri and Dhekelia|Akrotiri]], [[Cyprus]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder|Right midfield]]\n| youthyears1 = pre\u20131994\n| youthclubs1 = [[Swindon Town]]\n| years1 = 1994\u20131997\n| years2 = 1997\u20131999\n| years3 = 1999\u20132001\n| years4 = 2001\u20132003\n| years5 = 2003\u20132004\n| years6 = 2004\n| years7 = 2005\u20132007\n| years8 = 2011\n| clubs1 = [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n| clubs2 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| clubs3 = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n| clubs4 = [[Parramatta Power]]\n| clubs5 = [[Northern Spirit FC|Northern Spirit]]\n| clubs6 = [[Geylang United]]\n| clubs7 = [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]]\n| clubs8 = [[Lake Macquarie City FC|Lake Macquarie City]]\n| caps1 = 89\n| goals1 = 3\n| caps2 = 85\n| goals2 = 4\n| caps3 = 85\n| goals3 = 3\n| caps4 = 55\n| goals4 = 2\n| caps5 = 24\n| goals5 = 0\n| caps6 = \n| goals6 = 4\n| caps7 = 37\n| goals7 = 1\n| caps8 = 11\n| goals8 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1995\n| nationalteam1 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2004\n| managerclubs1 = [[Geylang United FC|Geylang United]]\n| manageryears2 = 2008\u20132009\n| managerclubs2 = [[Wellington Phoenix]] (asst.)\n| manageryears3 = 2009\u20132012\n| managerclubs3 = [[Newcastle Jets FC W-League]]\n| manageryears4 = 2013\u20132015\n| managerclubs4 = [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] (asst.)\n| manageryears5 = 2018\n| managerclubs5 = [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears6 = 2019 - current\n| managerclubs6 = [[Bonnyrigg White Eagles F.C.]]\n}}\n'''Wayne St John O'Sullivan''' (born February 25, 1974) is an Irish retired professional [[Association football|footballer]]. Since retiring as a player he has worked as a coach.\n\nBorn in Cyprus, O'Sullivan played youth football for [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] before making his professional debut with the club. In 2001, he moved to Australia, where he played in the [[National Soccer League]] and [[A-League]], as well as one season in Singapore.\n\nO'Sullivan represented [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland at youth level]].\n\nO'Sullivan is the current caretaker coach for [[A-League]] side [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\nO'Sullivan was part of the regular first eleven for [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]. At the time Plymouth were placed low in the [[Football League Third Division|Nationwide Division 3]] (now [[Football League Two]]), he along with [[Paul McGregor (footballer)|Paul McGregor]] and [[Martin Phillips (footballer)|Martin Phillips]] were considered the most consistent players at the time. But in the summer of 2000 he headed to Australia to continue his playing career.\n\nFollowing the demise of the old [[National Soccer League]] competition and the creation of the [[A-League]], O'Sullivan signed with [[Central Coast Mariners]] in late 2004 to play in the newly-formed A-League.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Soccer/Player-drain-as-Victory-delays/2004/12/14/1102787077306.html|title=Player drain as Victory delays|newspaper=[[The Age]]|date=15 December 2004|accessdate=14 April 2017|author=Lynch, Michael}}</ref> At the club, he was a favourite among fans for his tenacity and energy on the field. After an inconsistent 2006\u201307 season with The Mariners, during which he was often deployed as a right-back, instead of his preferred right-midfield position, the hard-working midfielder/defender was released.\n\nAlthough there is some controversy surrounding [[Lawrie McKinna]]'s decision to release O'Sullivan, it was believed by many in the Mariners camp that he was past his best and for the club to continue to grow in a developing league, his release was necessary.\n\n===International===\nO'Sullivan came on as a substitute for [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland under-21]] in a win over [[Latvia national under-21 football team|Latvia]] in [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] on 10 October 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/republic-of-ireland-v-latvia-10-october-1995-258874/|title=Republic of Ireland v Latvia, 10 October 1995|publisher=11v11.com|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref> He made a total of two appearances for the side.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindon-town-fc.co.uk/Person.asp?PersonID=OSULLIVW|title=Wayne O'Sullivan|publisher=[[Swindon Town F.C.]]|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nAfter being released by Central Coast Mariners, O'Sullivan had spent months trying to find a spot in another football team to continue his playing career, but was not successful.\n\nHe holds an Asian Federation Advance Level ([[FIFA]]) 'B' coaching licence and in July will graduate from Sydney University with a master's degree in education, specialising in coaching.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nOn Friday, 18 May 2007, O'Sullivan was named Assistant Coach for [[A-League]] club [[Wellington Phoenix]] on a two-year deal. He worked alongside [[Ricki Herbert]], [[Luciano Trani]] and former [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] goalkeeper [[Jonathan Gould]].\n\nOn Thursday, 21 November 2013, O'Sullivan was named Assistant Coach for the [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] on a contract until the end of the 2014&ndash;15 A-League season, working alongside newly appointed coach [[Phil Moss]].\n\nFollowing the immediate departure of Central Coast Mariner's Head Coach [[Paul Okon]], O'Sullivan was named as the caretaker coach until the end of the [[2017\u201318 A-League|2017\u201318 A-League season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/paul-okon-quits-as-mariners-boss-after-disappointing-a-league-campaign-20180320-p4z5b2.html|title=Paul Okon quits as Mariners boss after disappointing A-League campaign|first=Emma|last=Kemp|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn Thursday, 16 My 2019, O'Sullivan was appointed as new coach for the remainder of the 2019 [[National Premier Leagues NSW 2]] season with the [[Bonnyrigg White Eagles FC]]. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://footballnsw.com.au/2019/05/16/wayne-osullivan-appointed-new-bonnyrigg-white-eagles-coach/|title=WAYNE O\u2019SULLIVAN APPOINTED NEW BONNYRIGG WHITE EAGLES COACH|accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|6 May 2018}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|Nat\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]]\n|{{flagicon|Australia}}\n|align=left|20 March 2018\n|align=left|10 April 2018\n{{WDL|4|0|0|4}}\n|-\n!colspan=4|Total\n{{WDLtot|4|0|0|4}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;[[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n*[[Football League Second Division]]: [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393]]\n\n;[[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]]\n*[[A-League Pre-Season Challenge Cup]]: [[2005 A-League Pre-Season Challenge Cup|2005]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Plymouth Argyle F.C. Player of the Year]]: [[2000\u201301 Plymouth Argyle F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.swindon-town-fc.co.uk/Person.asp?PersonID=OSULLIVW Swindown Town FC]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110718025017/http://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/default.aspx?s=wellfc_news_item&id=17822 A-league Profile]\n* [http://www.cardiffcityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Welcome Cardiff City FC]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100801213543/http://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/default.aspx?s=aleague_team]\n* [http://www.lakemacquariecityfc.com]\n* [https://footballnsw.com.au/2019/05/16/wayne-osullivan-appointed-new-bonnyrigg-white-eagles-coach/]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Plymouth Argyle F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Central Coast Mariners FC head coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osullivan, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:National Soccer League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Central Coast Mariners FC players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C.